{"title_page": "Super-seeding", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=October 2012}}\nIn [[file sharing]], '''super-seeding''' (aka 'Initial Seeding') is an [[algorithm]] developed by John Hoffman for the [[BitTorrent (protocol)|BitTorrent communications protocol]] that helps downloaders become uploaders more quickly, but it introduces the danger of total seeding failure if there is only one downloader.\n\nThe algorithm applies when there is only one [[Glossary of BitTorrent terms#Seed|seed]] in the [[Glossary of BitTorrent terms#Swarm|swarm]]. By permitting each [[Glossary of BitTorrent terms#Downloader|downloader]] to [[download]] only specific parts of the [[Computer file|files]] listed in a [[Torrent file|torrent]], it allows peers to start [[Seeding (computing)|seeding]] more quickly.<ref>[http://www.bittorrent.org/beps/bep_0016.html BitTorrent.org]. Bittorrent.org (2008-02-25). Retrieved on 2011-12-03.</ref> Peers attached to a seed with super-seeding enabled therefore distribute pieces of the torrent file much more readily before they have completed the download themselves.<ref>http://www.torrentsecurity.com/news/a-lesson-in-seeding-and-super-seeding</ref><ref>https://wiki.vuze.com/w/Super_Seeding</ref>\n\nIn 2003, [[BitTornado]] became the first [[Comparison of BitTorrent clients|BitTorrent client]] to implement the algorithm.\n\n==Effects==\nTesting by one group found that super seeding can help save an upload ratio of around 20%. It works best when the upload speed of the seed is greater than that of individual peers.<ref name=\"Chen2008\">{{Citation| first1=Zhijia | last1=Chen| first2=Yang|last2=Chen|first3=Chuang|last3=Lin|last4=Nivargi|first4=V.|last5=Cao|first5=P.| contribution=Experimental Analysis of Super-Seeding in BitTorrent| title=ICC '08. IEEE International Conference on Communications, 2008. ICC '08.| publisher=IEEE| place=Beijing, China| page=65| date=2008-05-30| doi= 10.1109/ICC.2008.20}}</ref>\n\nSuper seeding transfers stall when there is only one downloading client. The seeders will not send more data until a second client receives the data. To avoid this, [[rTorrent]] continues to offer more pieces to the peers without waiting for confirmation, until it is uploading at its configured capacity.<ref>[http://libtorrent.rakshasa.no/wiki/RTorrentInitialSeeding RTorrentInitialSeeding \u2013 The libTorrent and rTorrent Project]. Libtorrent.rakshasa.no. Retrieved on 2011-12-03.</ref> This improves the upload speed until enough peers have joined the swarm, at the cost of not being able to detect cheating peers, who engage in such anti-social actions as downloading only from seeds, downloading from the fastest peers, or advertising false pieces.<ref>https://torrentfreak.com/cheating-bittorrent/</ref>\n\n== Supporting clients ==\n* [[ABC (Yet Another BitTorrent Client)]]\n*BiglyBT\n* [[BitComet]] (Feature added in v.1.16. Renamed to Initial-Seeding in v.1.17.)\n* [[BitSpirit]]\n* [[BitTornado]]\n* [[BitTorrent (software)|BitTorrent]] version 6.0\n* [[Deluge (software)|Deluge]] since version 2.00\n* Halite<ref>http://www.binarynotions.com/halite-bittorrent-client/</ref>\n* [[KTorrent]] 4.1\n*[[libtorrent]]\n* [[qBittorrent]]\n* [[rTorrent]] version [http://rakshasa.no/pipermail/libtorrent-devel/2008-May/001586.html 0.8.2]\n* [[Tixati]] since version [http://www.tixati.com/news/index.html 1.34]\n* [[\u03bcTorrent]] (Named \"Initial Seeding\")\n* [[Vuze]] (formerly Azureus)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://bittornado.com/docs/superseed.txt Description of original super-seed algorithm in BitTornado]\n* [http://www.zeropaid.com/news/8945/STUDY:+'Examining+the+Myths+and+Facts+Concerning+BitComet+Behavior' Report by Robb Toploski] (''Issue #4 & 5 are regarding Super Seeding'')\n\n{{BitTorrent}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Super-seeding}}\n[[Category:BitTorrent]]\n\n[[de:BitTorrent#Superseeding]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=October 2012}}\nIn [[file sharing]], '''super-seeding''' (aka 'Initial Seeding') is an [[algorithm]] developed by John Hoffman for the [[BitTorrent (protocol)|BitTorrent communications protocol]] that helps downloaders to be able to become uploaders more quickly, but it introduces the danger of total seeding failure if there is only one downloader.\n\nThe algorithm applies to a scenario in which there is only one [[Glossary of BitTorrent terms#Seed|seed]] in the [[Glossary of BitTorrent terms#Swarm|swarm]]. By permitting each [[Glossary of BitTorrent terms#Downloader|downloader]] to [[download]] only specific parts of the [[Computer file|files]] listed in a [[Torrent file|torrent]], it equips peers to begin [[Seeding (computing)|seeding]] sooner.<ref>[http://www.bittorrent.org/beps/bep_0016.html BitTorrent.org]. Bittorrent.org (2008-02-25). Retrieved on 2011-12-03.</ref>  Peers attached to a seed with super-seeding enabled therefore distribute pieces of the torrent file much more readily before they have completed download themselves.<ref>http://www.torrentsecurity.com/news/a-lesson-in-seeding-and-super-seeding</ref><ref>https://wiki.vuze.com/w/Super_Seeding</ref>\n\nIn 2003, [[BitTornado]] became the first [[Comparison of BitTorrent clients|BitTorrent client]] to implement the algorithm.\n\n==Effects==\nTesting by one group found that super seeding can help save an upload ratio of around 20%. It works best when the upload speed of the seed is greater than that of individual peers.<ref name=\"Chen2008\">{{Citation| first1=Zhijia | last1=Chen| first2=Yang|last2=Chen|first3=Chuang|last3=Lin|last4=Nivargi|first4=V.|last5=Cao|first5=P.| contribution=Experimental Analysis of Super-Seeding in BitTorrent| title=ICC '08. IEEE International Conference on Communications, 2008. ICC '08.| publisher=IEEE| place=Beijing, China| page=65| date=2008-05-30| doi= 10.1109/ICC.2008.20}}</ref>\n\nSuper seeding transfers stall when there is only one downloading client. The seeders will not send more data until a second client receives the data. To avoid this, [[rTorrent]] continues to offer more pieces to the peers without waiting for confirmation, until it is uploading at its configured capacity.<ref>[http://libtorrent.rakshasa.no/wiki/RTorrentInitialSeeding RTorrentInitialSeeding \u2013 The libTorrent and rTorrent Project]. Libtorrent.rakshasa.no. Retrieved on 2011-12-03.</ref> This improves the upload speed until enough peers have joined the swarm, at the cost of not being able to detect cheating peers, who engage in such anti-social actions as downloading only from seeds, downloading from the fastest peers, or advertising false pieces.<ref>https://torrentfreak.com/cheating-bittorrent/</ref>\n\n== Supporting clients ==\n* [[ABC (Yet Another BitTorrent Client)]]\n*BiglyBT\n* [[BitComet]] (Feature added in v.1.16. Renamed to Initial-Seeding in v.1.17.)\n* [[BitSpirit]]\n* [[BitTornado]]\n* [[BitTorrent (software)|BitTorrent]] version 6.0\n* [[Deluge (software)|Deluge]] since version 2.00\n* Halite<ref>http://www.binarynotions.com/halite-bittorrent-client/</ref>\n* [[KTorrent]] 4.1\n*[[libtorrent]]\n* [[qBittorrent]]\n* [[rTorrent]] version [http://rakshasa.no/pipermail/libtorrent-devel/2008-May/001586.html 0.8.2]\n* [[Tixati]] since version [http://www.tixati.com/news/index.html 1.34]\n* [[\u03bcTorrent]] (Named \"Initial Seeding\")\n* [[Vuze]] (formerly Azureus)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://bittornado.com/docs/superseed.txt Description of original super-seed algorithm in BitTornado]\n* [http://www.zeropaid.com/news/8945/STUDY:+'Examining+the+Myths+and+Facts+Concerning+BitComet+Behavior' Report by Robb Toploski] (''Issue #4 & 5 are regarding Super Seeding'')\n\n{{BitTorrent}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Super-seeding}}\n[[Category:BitTorrent]]\n\n[[de:BitTorrent#Superseeding]]\n", "name_user": "Filterfish", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super-seeding"}
{"title_page": "Marta Xargay", "text_new": "{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Marta Xargay\n| image = \n| number = 10\n| position = [[Shooting guard]]\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lbs = 157\n| league = [[Liga Femenina de Baloncesto|LF]]\n| team = [[Uni Girona CB]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1990|12|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Girona]], Spain\n| nationality = Spanish\n| career_start = 2009\n| career_end = \n| highlights = *[[EuroLeague Women|EuroLeague]] Champion (2011)\n*2x [[Liga Femenina de Baloncesto|Spanish League]] champion (2011, 2013)\n*3x [[Copa de la Reina de Baloncesto|Spanish Cup]] champion (2012, 1014, 2015)\n*3x [[Czech Women's Basketball League|Czech League]] champion (2016, 2017, 2018)\n| years1 = 1996\u20132003\n| team1 = C.E. Vedruna\n| years2 = 2003\u20132005\n| team2 = C.E.S.E.T.\n| years3 = 2005\u20132009\n| team3 = [[Uni Girona CB]]\n| years4 = 2009\u20132015\n| team4 = [[CB Avenida]]\n| years5 = 2015\u20132016\n| team5 = [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| years6 = 2015\u20132018\n| team6 = [[USK Praha (women's basketball)|USK Praha]]\n| years7 = 2018\u20132019\n| team7 = [[Dynamo Kursk]]\n| years8 = 2020-\n| team8 = [[Uni Girona CB]]\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{bkw|ESP}}}}\n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup|World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2014 FIBA World Championship for Women|2014 Turkey]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2018 FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup|2018 Spain]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[EuroBasket Women|EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[EuroBasket Women 2013|2013 France]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[EuroBasket Women 2017|2017 Czech Republic]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIBA Women's EuroBasket 2019|2019 Serbia/Latvia]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[EuroBasket Women 2015|2015 Hungary/Romania]]|}}\n}}\n'''Marta Xargay Casademont''' (born 20 December 1990) is a Spanish professional [[basketball]] player. She played for [[Phoenix Mercury]] of the [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]], and currently for the Spanish team [[Uni Girona CB]] and the [[Spain women's national basketball team]]. She has represented national team since [[EuroBasket Women 2011]] competition.<ref>[http://www.fibaeurope.com/cid_KNce8jInH7Qj1EsyH5rjn2.compID_jr6ZiXqeGhMBtfq1yxqV83.roundID_7843.season_2011.teamID_96446.playerID_57672.html FIBA Europe profile]</ref> She won [[EuroLeague Women 2010\u201311]] with Perfumer\u00edas Avenida Baloncesto. She left Spain in 2015, joining both USK Praha of the [[Czech Women's Basketball League|Czech League]] in 2015 and the Phoenix Mercury of the [[WNBA]] on 11 February 2015.<ref>[http://www.wnba.com/mercury/news/xargay_150211.html Mercury Sign Guard Marta Xargay] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214031638/http://www.wnba.com/mercury/news/xargay_150211.html |date=14 February 2015 }}</ref> In September 2018 she signed for [[Dynamo Kursk]] of the [[Russian Women's Basketball Premier League|Russian Premier League]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/baloncesto/mundial-femenino/2018/09/14/5b9ba2fee2704e42a08b45e7.html Marca.com (in Spanish)]</ref>, and in January 2020 she returned to his youth club [[Uni Girona CB]].\n\n==Club career==\nXargay started playing basketball from a young age in clubs in her hometown [[Girona]], entering the youth levels of [[Uni Girona CB]] at 14 and making it to the senior team and the Spanish [[Liga Femenina 2 de Baloncesto|second tier]]. In 2009 she signed for [[CB Avenida]] from [[Salamanca]], where in the following six seasons she won two [[Liga Femenina de Baloncesto|leagues]], three [[Copa de la Reina de Baloncesto|cups]] and one [[2010\u201311 EuroLeague Women|EuroLeague]].\n\nDuring 2015 and 2016 she played both in the [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wnba.com/player/marta-xargay-casademont/|title=Marta Xargay Casademont \u2013 WNBA.com \u2013 Official Site of the WNBA|work=WNBA.com \u2013 Official Site of the WNBA|access-date=3 October 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> with [[Phoenix Mercury]] and the European season with [[USK Praha (women's basketball)|USK Praha]], where she won the 2016, 2017 and 2018 [[Czech Women's Basketball League|Czech League]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eurobasket.com/Czech-Republic/basketball-League-ZBL_2016-2017.asp?women=1|title=ZBL_2016-2017 Basketball League CZECH-REPUBLIC \u2013 eurobasket|work=www.eurobasket.com|access-date=3 October 2017}}</ref> Due to her commitment to the [[Spain women's national basketball team|Spain national team]], she opted not to play in the WNBA in 2017 or 2018. She played for one and a half seasons in [[Russia]]n team [[Dynamo Kursk]], before returning to [[Uni Girona CB]] in January 2020. <ref>https://www.diaridegirona.cat/esports/2020/01/07/marta-xargay-torna-girona-quedar/1022485.html</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===WNBA===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Season\n!Team\n!GP\n!MPP\n!PPP\n!RPP\n!APP\n|-\n|2015\n|[[Phoenix Mercury]]\n|20\n|17.5\n|3.9\n|1.8\n|2.4\n|-\n|2016\n|[[Phoenix Mercury]]\n|15\n|19.8\n|5.7\n|1.7\n|2.7\n|}\n\n===EuroLeague and EuroCup statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#afe6ba; width:3em;\"|\n|[[EuroLeague Women|EuroLeague winner]]\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Season\n!Team\n!GP\n!MPP\n!PPP\n!RPP\n!APP\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 EuroLeague Women|2009\u201310 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Halc\u00f3n Avenida]]\n|13\n|10.5\n|2.0\n|1.0\n|1.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;background:#afe6ba;\"|[[2010\u201311 EuroLeague Women|2010\u201311 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Halc\u00f3n Avenida]]\n|17\n|13.7\n|3.5\n|1.3\n|0.9\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 EuroLeague Women|2011\u201312 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Perfumer\u00edas Avenida]]\n|14\n|25.1\n|6.0\n|3.0\n|2.7\n|-\n||[[2012\u201313 EuroLeague Women|2012\u201313 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Perfumer\u00edas Avenida]]\n|14\n|26.1\n|7.9\n|3.1\n|2.9\n|-\n||[[2013\u201314 EuroLeague Women|2013\u201314 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Perfumer\u00edas Avenida]]\n|13\n|30.9\n|8.5\n|4.2\n|4.7\n|-\n||[[2014\u201315 EuroLeague Women|2014\u201315 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Perfumer\u00edas Avenida]]\n|16\n|28.1\n|8.1\n|3.6\n|3.3\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 EuroLeague Women|2015\u201316 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|CZE}} [[USK Praha (women's basketball)|ZVVZ USK Praha]]\n|17\n|19.7\n|4.9\n|2.1\n|2.0\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 EuroLeague Women|2016\u201317 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|CZE}} [[USK Praha (women's basketball)|ZVVZ USK Praha]]\n|19\n|30.8\n|11.0\n|3.3\n|3.4\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 EuroLeague Women|2017\u201318 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|CZE}} [[USK Praha (women's basketball)|ZVVZ USK Praha]]\n|15\n|36.0\n|11.6\n|4.0\n|6.6\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 EuroLeague Women|2018\u201319 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Dynamo Kursk]]\n|17\n|20.9\n|5.1\n|1.9\n|3.1\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[2019\u201320 EuroLeague Women|2019\u201320 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Dynamo Kursk]]\n|8\n|24.6\n|4.0\n|2.9\n|2.5\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Uni Girona CB|Spar CityLift Girona]]\n|6\n|21.4\n|7.3\n|2.7\n|2.7\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 EuroCup Women|2019\u201320 EuroCup]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Uni Girona CB|Spar CityLift Girona]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==National team==\nXargay started playing with [[Spain women's national basketball team|Spain]]'s youth teams at 16, winning a total of five medals from 2006 to 2010. She made her debut with the senior team in 2011. Up to 2017, she had 107 caps and 8 PPG,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://seleccionfemenina.feb.es/|title=Selecci\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola Absoluta Femenina de Baloncesto|website=seleccionfemenina.feb.es|access-date=3 October 2017}}</ref> participating in the [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|Rio 2016]] Olympics, one [[FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup|World Championships]] and four [[EuroBasket Women|European Championships]]:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/p/q/Marta%20XARGAY/pid/57672/_//players.html|title=archive.fiba.com: Players|website=archive.fiba.com|access-date=3 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n* [[File:Gold medal icon.svg|16x16px]] [[2006 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship for Women|2006 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship]] (''youth'')\n* [[File:Silver medal icon.svg|16x16px]] [[2007 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship for Women|2007 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship]] (''youth'')\n* 5th [[2008 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship for Women|2008 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship]] (''youth'')\n* [[File:Silver medal icon.svg|16x16px]] [[2009 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship for Women|2009 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship]] (''youth'')\n* [[File:Silver medal icon.svg|16x16px]] [[2009 FIBA Under-19 World Championship for Women|2009 FIBA Under-19 World Championship]] (''youth'') ('''''MVP''''')\n* [[File:Silver medal icon.svg|16x16px]] [[2010 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship for Women|2010 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship]] (''youth'')\n* 9th [[EuroBasket Women 2011|2011 Eurobasket]]\n* [[File:Gold medal europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket Women 2013|2013 Eurobasket]]\n* [[File:Silver medal world centered-2.svg|16x16px]] [[2014 FIBA World Championship for Women|2014 World Championship]]\n* [[File:Bronze medal europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket Women 2015|2015 Eurobasket]]\n* [[File:Silver medal olympic.svg|16x16px]] [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2016 Summer Olympics]]\n* [[File:Gold medal europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket Women 2017|2017 Eurobasket]]\n* [[File:Bronze medal world centered-2.svg|16x16px]] [[2018 FIBA World Championship for Women|2018 World Championship]]\n* [[File:Gold medal europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket Women 2019|2019 Eurobasket]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fibaeurope.com/cid_KNce8jInH7Qj1EsyH5rjn2.compID_jr6ZiXqeGhMBtfq1yxqV83.roundID_7843.season_2011.teamID_96446.playerID_57672.html FIBA Europe profile]\n*{{Sports-reference}}\n*{{FIBA profile}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title = Spain squads\n| bg = #DB000D\n| fg = #FBEA0E\n| bordercolor = Black\n| list1 =\n{{Spain Squad 2013 FIBA Europe Championship for Women}}\n{{Spain Squad 2014 FIBA World Championship for Women}}\n{{Spain Women Basketball Squad 2016 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Spain Squad 2017 FIBA Europe Championship for Women}}\n{{Spain Squad 2018 FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Halc\u00f3n Avenida Baloncesto 2010\u201311 Euroleague Women champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Xargay, Marta}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Catalan women's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic basketball players of Spain]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in basketball]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Spain]]\n[[Category:Phoenix Mercury players]]\n[[Category:People from Girona]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate basketball people in Russia]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Spanish women's basketball players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Marta Xargay\n| image = \n| number = 10\n| position = [[Shooting guard]]\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lbs = 157\n| league = [[Liga Femenina de Baloncesto|LF]]\n| team = [[Uni Girona CB]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1990|12|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Girona]], Spain\n| nationality = Spanish\n| career_start = 2009\n| career_end = \n| highlights = *[[EuroLeague Women|EuroLeague]] Champion (2011)\n*2x [[Liga Femenina de Baloncesto|Spanish League]] champion (2011, 2013)\n*3x [[Copa de la Reina de Baloncesto|Spanish Cup]] champion (2012, 1014, 2015)\n*3x [[Czech Women's Basketball League|Czech League]] champion (2016, 2017, 2018)\n| years1 = 1996\u20132003\n| team1 = C.E. Vedruna\n| years2 = 2003\u20132005\n| team2 = C.E.S.E.T.\n| years3 = 2005\u20132009\n| team3 = [[Uni Girona CB]]\n| years4 = 2009\u20132015\n| team4 = [[CB Avenida]]\n| years5 = 2015\u20132016\n| team5 = [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| years6 = 2015\u20132018\n| team6 = [[USK Praha (women's basketball)|USK Praha]]\n| years7 = 2018\u20132019\n| team7 = [[Dynamo Kursk]]\n| years8 = 2020-\n| team8 = [[Uni Girona CB]]\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{bkw|ESP}}}}\n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup|World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2014 FIBA World Championship for Women|2014 Turkey]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2018 FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup|2018 Spain]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[EuroBasket Women|EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[EuroBasket Women 2013|2013 France]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[EuroBasket Women 2017|2017 Czech Republic]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIBA Women's EuroBasket 2019|2019 Serbia/Latvia]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[EuroBasket Women 2015|2015 Hungary/Romania]]|}}\n}}\n'''Marta Xargay Casademont''' (born 20 December 1990) is a Spanish professional [[basketball]] player. She played for [[Phoenix Mercury]] of the [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]], and currently for the Spanish team [[Uni Girona CB]] and the [[Spain women's national basketball team]]. She has represented national team since [[EuroBasket Women 2011]] competition.<ref>[http://www.fibaeurope.com/cid_KNce8jInH7Qj1EsyH5rjn2.compID_jr6ZiXqeGhMBtfq1yxqV83.roundID_7843.season_2011.teamID_96446.playerID_57672.html FIBA Europe profile]</ref> She won [[EuroLeague Women 2010\u201311]] with Perfumer\u00edas Avenida Baloncesto. She left Spain in 2015, joining both USK Praha of the [[Czech Women's Basketball League|Czech League]] in 2015 and the Phoenix Mercury of the [[WNBA]] on 11 February 2015.<ref>[http://www.wnba.com/mercury/news/xargay_150211.html Mercury Sign Guard Marta Xargay] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214031638/http://www.wnba.com/mercury/news/xargay_150211.html |date=14 February 2015 }}</ref> In September 2018 she signed for [[Dynamo Kursk]] of the [[Russian Women's Basketball Premier League|Russian Premier League]].<ref>[http://www.marca.com/baloncesto/mundial-femenino/2018/09/14/5b9ba2fee2704e42a08b45e7.html Marca.com (in Spanish)]</ref>, and in January 2020 she returned to his youth club [[Uni Girona CB]].\n\n==Club career==\nXargay started playing basketball from a young age in clubs in her hometown [[Girona]], entering the youth levels of [[Uni Girona CB]] at 14 and making it to the senior team and the Spanish [[Liga Femenina 2 de Baloncesto|second tier]]. In 2009 she signed for [[CB Avenida]] from [[Salamanca]], where in the following six seasons she won two [[Liga Femenina de Baloncesto|leagues]], three [[Copa de la Reina de Baloncesto|cups]] and one [[2010\u201311 EuroLeague Women|EuroLeague]].\n\nDuring 2015 and 2016 she played both in the [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wnba.com/player/marta-xargay-casademont/|title=Marta Xargay Casademont \u2013 WNBA.com \u2013 Official Site of the WNBA|work=WNBA.com \u2013 Official Site of the WNBA|access-date=3 October 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> with [[Phoenix Mercury]] and the European season with [[USK Praha (women's basketball)|USK Praha]], where she won the 2016, 2017 and 2018 [[Czech Women's Basketball League|Czech League]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eurobasket.com/Czech-Republic/basketball-League-ZBL_2016-2017.asp?women=1|title=ZBL_2016-2017 Basketball League CZECH-REPUBLIC \u2013 eurobasket|work=www.eurobasket.com|access-date=3 October 2017}}</ref> Due to her commitment to the [[Spain women's national basketball team|Spain national team]], she opted not to play in the WNBA in 2017 or 2018. She played for one and a half seasons in [[Russia]]n team [[Dynamo Kursk]], before returning to [[Uni Girona CB]] in January 2020. <ref>https://www.diaridegirona.cat/esports/2020/01/07/marta-xargay-torna-girona-quedar/1022485.html</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===WNBA===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Season\n!Team\n!GP\n!MPP\n!PPP\n!RPP\n!APP\n|-\n|2015\n|[[Phoenix Mercury]]\n|20\n|17.5\n|3.9\n|1.8\n|2.4\n|-\n|2016\n|[[Phoenix Mercury]]\n|15\n|19.8\n|5.7\n|1.7\n|2.7\n|}\n\n===EuroLeague and EuroCup statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#afe6ba; width:3em;\"|\n|[[EuroLeague Women|EuroLeague winner]]\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Season\n!Team\n!GP\n!MPP\n!PPP\n!RPP\n!APP\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 EuroLeague Women|2009\u201310 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Halc\u00f3n Avenida]]\n|13\n|10.5\n|2.0\n|1.0\n|1.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;background:#afe6ba;\"|[[2010\u201311 EuroLeague Women|2010\u201311 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Halc\u00f3n Avenida]]\n|17\n|13.7\n|3.5\n|1.3\n|0.9\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 EuroLeague Women|2011\u201312 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Perfumer\u00edas Avenida]]\n|14\n|25.1\n|6.0\n|3.0\n|2.7\n|-\n||[[2012\u201313 EuroLeague Women|2012\u201313 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Perfumer\u00edas Avenida]]\n|14\n|26.1\n|7.9\n|3.1\n|2.9\n|-\n||[[2013\u201314 EuroLeague Women|2013\u201314 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Perfumer\u00edas Avenida]]\n|13\n|30.9\n|8.5\n|4.2\n|4.7\n|-\n||[[2014\u201315 EuroLeague Women|2014\u201315 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[CB Avenida|Perfumer\u00edas Avenida]]\n|16\n|28.1\n|8.1\n|3.6\n|3.3\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 EuroLeague Women|2015\u201316 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|CZE}} [[USK Praha (women's basketball)|ZVVZ USK Praha]]\n|17\n|19.7\n|4.9\n|2.1\n|2.0\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 EuroLeague Women|2016\u201317 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|CZE}} [[USK Praha (women's basketball)|ZVVZ USK Praha]]\n|19\n|30.8\n|11.0\n|3.3\n|3.4\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 EuroLeague Women|2017\u201318 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|CZE}} [[USK Praha (women's basketball)|ZVVZ USK Praha]]\n|15\n|36.0\n|11.6\n|4.0\n|6.6\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 EuroLeague Women|2018\u201319 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Dynamo Kursk]]\n|17\n|20.9\n|5.1\n|1.9\n|3.1\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 EuroLeague Women|2019\u201320 EuroLeague]]\n|{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Dynamo Kursk]]\n|8\n|24.6\n|4.0\n|2.9\n|2.5\n|-\n|\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Uni Girona CB|Spar CityLift Girona]]\n|6\n|21.4\n|7.3\n|2.7\n|2.7\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 EuroCup Women|2019\u201320 EuroCup]]\n|{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Uni Girona CB|Spar CityLift Girona]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==National team==\nXargay started playing with [[Spain women's national basketball team|Spain]]'s youth teams at 16, winning a total of five medals from 2006 to 2010. She made her debut with the senior team in 2011. Up to 2017, she had 107 caps and 8 PPG,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://seleccionfemenina.feb.es/|title=Selecci\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola Absoluta Femenina de Baloncesto|website=seleccionfemenina.feb.es|access-date=3 October 2017}}</ref> participating in the [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|Rio 2016]] Olympics, one [[FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup|World Championships]] and four [[EuroBasket Women|European Championships]]:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/p/q/Marta%20XARGAY/pid/57672/_//players.html|title=archive.fiba.com: Players|website=archive.fiba.com|access-date=3 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n* [[File:Gold medal icon.svg|16x16px]] [[2006 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship for Women|2006 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship]] (''youth'')\n* [[File:Silver medal icon.svg|16x16px]] [[2007 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship for Women|2007 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship]] (''youth'')\n* 5th [[2008 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship for Women|2008 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship]] (''youth'')\n* [[File:Silver medal icon.svg|16x16px]] [[2009 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship for Women|2009 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship]] (''youth'')\n* [[File:Silver medal icon.svg|16x16px]] [[2009 FIBA Under-19 World Championship for Women|2009 FIBA Under-19 World Championship]] (''youth'') ('''''MVP''''')\n* [[File:Silver medal icon.svg|16x16px]] [[2010 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship for Women|2010 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship]] (''youth'')\n* 9th [[EuroBasket Women 2011|2011 Eurobasket]]\n* [[File:Gold medal europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket Women 2013|2013 Eurobasket]]\n* [[File:Silver medal world centered-2.svg|16x16px]] [[2014 FIBA World Championship for Women|2014 World Championship]]\n* [[File:Bronze medal europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket Women 2015|2015 Eurobasket]]\n* [[File:Silver medal olympic.svg|16x16px]] [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2016 Summer Olympics]]\n* [[File:Gold medal europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket Women 2017|2017 Eurobasket]]\n* [[File:Bronze medal world centered-2.svg|16x16px]] [[2018 FIBA World Championship for Women|2018 World Championship]]\n* [[File:Gold medal europe.svg|16x16px]] [[EuroBasket Women 2019|2019 Eurobasket]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fibaeurope.com/cid_KNce8jInH7Qj1EsyH5rjn2.compID_jr6ZiXqeGhMBtfq1yxqV83.roundID_7843.season_2011.teamID_96446.playerID_57672.html FIBA Europe profile]\n*{{Sports-reference}}\n*{{FIBA profile}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title = Spain squads\n| bg = #DB000D\n| fg = #FBEA0E\n| bordercolor = Black\n| list1 =\n{{Spain Squad 2013 FIBA Europe Championship for Women}}\n{{Spain Squad 2014 FIBA World Championship for Women}}\n{{Spain Women Basketball Squad 2016 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Spain Squad 2017 FIBA Europe Championship for Women}}\n{{Spain Squad 2018 FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Halc\u00f3n Avenida Baloncesto 2010\u201311 Euroleague Women champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Xargay, Marta}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Catalan women's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic basketball players of Spain]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in basketball]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Spain]]\n[[Category:Phoenix Mercury players]]\n[[Category:People from Girona]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate basketball people in Russia]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Spanish women's basketball players]]\n", "name_user": "D0nc0s", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marta_Xargay"}
{"title_page": "Thyagaraja Temple, Tiruvottiyur", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox Hindu temple\n| name               = Thiyagaraja Swamy Temple\n| image              = thyagaraswamy6.jpg\n| alt                =\n| caption            =\n| map_type           = <!-- India Tamil Nadu -->\n| map_caption        = Location in Tamil Nadu\n| coordinates        = {{coord|13|9|N|80|18|E|type:landmark_region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| native_name        = Thiruvotriyur Thiyagaraja Swamy Temple\n| country            = [[India]]\n| state              = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| district           = [[Chennai district|Chennai]]\n| location           = [[Thiruvotriyur]], [[Chennai]]\n| elevation_m        =\n| deity              = Thiyagaraja Swamy, Aadhipureeswarar, and Thiruvottrieswarar ([[Shiva]])\nVadivudaiamman aka Tripurasundari ([[parvathi]])\n| facade_direction   = \n| temple_tank        = Brahma Theeertham, Adisesha Theertham\n| tower              = \n| festivals          = Maasi Bramotsavam, Vasantha urchavam, Shivarathiri, Thai poosam, Navarathiri, Skandashashti, Aadi pooram, Arudhra darshan, Vattaparaiamman urchavam, Navarathiri and Pournami days\n| architecture       = [[Dravidian architecture]]\n| temple_quantity    =\n| monument_quantity  =\n| inscriptions       =\n| year_completed     =\n| creator            =\n| website            =\n}}\n\n'''Thyagaraja Temple''' (also called as '''Vadivudai Amman Temple''') is a [[Hindu temple]] dedicated to [[Hindu god]] [[Shiva]]. It is located in [[Tiruvottiyur]] in the northern part of [[Chennai]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]. The temple is revered by the ''[[Tevaram]]'' hymns of [[Saivite|Saiva]] [[nayanars]], the 7th century [[Tamil people|Tamil]] saint poets and classified as [[Paadal Petra Sthalam]].All the Three of Thevaram Moovar(Appar, Samandar and Sundarar) has rendered Thevaram songs in this temple. The temple is closely associated with the saint poet [[Sundarar]] and [[Pattinathar]]. The temple has been in vogue from the [[Pallava]] times of the 7th century and widely expanded by [[Chola]] kings during the 11th century. The temple has a seven tiered gateway tower, a tank, with the overall temple area covering 1 acre. The temple is administered by the Hindu Religious and Endowment Board of the [[Government of Tamil Nadu]]. The temple draws parallel with the [[Thyagaraja Temple, Tiruvarur|Thygaraja temple]] in [[Tiruvarur]] as both the temples were expanded by [[Rajendra Chola I]] and both have the same dance poses of Shiva. The temple is one of the 51 ''Sakthi Peetams'' in the country.<ref name=\"InscriptionsInBadState\">{{cite news \n  | last = Ramakrishnan \n  | first = Deepa H. \n  | title = 'Tiruvottiyur temple inscriptions in a bad state'\n  | newspaper = The Hindu\n  | location = Chennai\n  | pages = 2\n  | language = \n  | publisher = Kasturi & Sons\n  | date = 8 May 2019\n  | url = https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/tiruvottiyur-temple-inscriptions-in-a-bad-state/article27062723.ece\n  | accessdate = 12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legend==\n[[File:Thiuvotriyur3.jpg|Shrine of Vadivudai Amman|left|200px|thumb]]\n[[Brahm\u0101]] is the [[Hinduism|Hindu]] god of creation and one of the three primary gods of Hinduism, the other two being [[Vishnu|Vi\u1e63\u0146u]] and [[Shiva|\u015aiva]].  He created the Gods and demons - both these groups fight against each other. While the demons, called ''asuras'' use muscle power, the Gods called ''devas'' use the power of ''[[Veda]]'', the sacred texts.{{sfn|Eisenstadt| 1984| p= 22}} Once, two demons, Madhu and Kaithaba tricked the gods to steal the ''Veda'', chopped it to pieces and hid it in the bottom of the sea. [[Vishnu]] fought the demons, but could not defeat them.{{sfn|Eisenstadt| 1984| p= 22}}  He prayed to Shiva and [[Parvathi]] and with the accomplishment, he was able to defeat the demons.{{sfn|Eisenstadt| 1984| p= 22}} He took the form of ''[[Matsya Purana|Matsya]]'', a fish to search the ''Veda''.{{sfn|Eisenstadt| 1984| p= 22}}  The recovered ''Veda'' from the bottom of the sea was brought to the deity at this temple, who reunited and purified it.{{sfn|Eisenstadt| 1984| p= 22}} The wishing tree of gods, ''makizha'' tree, became the sacred tree of the temple.{{sfn|Eisenstadt| 1984| p= 13}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:Thiuvotriyur1.jpg|Shrine of Tiruvoteeswarar located behind the main shrine in the second prcinct|250px|thumb]]\nThe temple was the centre of learning, with the halls inside the temple acting as venue for religious discourses in subjects like ''vyakarna'' (translation), ''Somasiddantha'' (philosophy) and Panini's grammar.{{sfn|Ayyar |1991| p=18}}{{sfn|Madras Tercentenary Celebration Committee|1994| p= 357}} There was a hermitage attached to the temple during the 9th century, presided over by Caturananas Pandithar.{{sfn|Madras Tercentenary Celebration Committee|1994| p= 357}} The temple also had philosophical discourses and expositions on grammar.{{sfn|Kamath |2000| p= 275}} There are references to recital of ''Prabhakara'', ''Rudra'', ''Yamala'', ''Purana'', ''Sivadharma'', ''Panchanga'' and ''Bharata''.{{sfn|Ayyar |1991| p=18}}  Lands were granted to learned scholars and their generation like ''Vedavritti'', ''Bhattavriti'', ''Vaidyavritti'' and ''Archanavritti''.{{sfn|Ayyar |1991| p=18}}\n\nThere are a number of inscriptions inside the temple dating back to [[Pallava]] period.{{sfn|Madras Tercentenary Celebration Committee|1994| p= 357}} [[Sankaracharya]], the 8th century scholar in the ''[[advaita]]'' school of [[Hinduism]] is believed to have visited the temple to put down the power of evil. The temple was originally built by [[Pallavas]] and later rebuilt by [[Rajendra Chola I]].{{sfn|Kamath |2000| p= 275}}  The inscription dating 954 CE, the fifth year of the Chola king [[Gandaraditya]] indicates 90 sheep for burning lamps and ''ilavilaku'', a lamp made in [[Sri Lanka]]).{{sfn|C.| 2003| p= 261}} The inscriptions dating from 1046 CE reveal that 64 bronze ''nayanmar'' statues were installed in the temple.{{sfn|Dehejia| 1990| pp= 123-124}} There were equal number of dancing girls called ''[[Devadasi]]'' in the temple, who were divided into two groups - the ''valankai dasis'' danced for Thyagaraja, while the ''idangai dasis'' danced for Vadivudaiamman.{{sfn|Ghose |1996| p= 33}} During the reign of the [[Malik Kafur]], much of the temple was destroyed and the bronze idols present now in the temple were installed during the [[Vijayanagara Empire|Vijayanagara]] period of the 15th century.{{sfn|Dehejia| 1990| pp= 123-124}} A 13th-century inscription indicates the practise of animal sacrifice to the goddess, which continued along with offering intoxicating drink till the early 2000s.{{sfn|Hastings| 2003| p= 92}} Famous saints like [[Pattinathar]], Topeswamigal and Ramalinga Swamigal lived in this town and prayed Thyagaraja in this temple. This place is also home to Thiruvottiyur Thyagayyar who is a carnatic composer and poet.{{sfn|Meena, 1974|p=47}} The temple had been a centre of learning as seen from the inscriptions in the temple. The inscriptions indicate specific subjects like ''Purvamimansa'' styled as ''Pravahakarma''. There were also provisions made for feeding and maintaining for teachers and students.{{sfn|Tyagi, 2013|pp=140\u2013144}}\n\n==The Temple==\n[[File:thyagaraswamy1.jpg|The ''gopuram'' of the temple|200px|left|thumb]]\n\nThe presiding deity is Aadhipureeswarar is in the form of a mud mound{{sfn|Hastings| 2003| p= 92}} covered by an armour. On the day of the full moon of the Tamil month ''karthigai'', the armour is removed and the representation of the god is visible to devotees. The Lord is anointed with ''punugu'', ''javvadhu'', and ''sampirani'' oils. There is a [[Durga]] shrine in the northern side of the temple. Inside the main temple complex - Just opposite to the main shrine we find the [[Nataraja]] shrine and in the koshta is the [[Ganapati]] Shrine. The Ganapati is known as Gunalaya Ganapati (abode of bliss) and as we circumbulate the shrine we find the  idol of [[Adi Shankara]] -just wee behind the main Shrine inside the Complex. We also find deities like [[Subrahmanya]] installed there. The [[Dakshinamurthy]] statue is in the Northern Koshta facing south and we come to the Sub complex Shrine of [[Kali]]. Adi Shankara is said to have installed a chakra to calm down the Devi and to make her Sowmya roopi (Calm and resplendent). To this day - a select group of Nampoothiri Families perform the pooja and aradhana to this Lord and Goddess as desired by Adi Shankara.\n\nThe name of the goddess at this temple is Vadivudaiamman alias Tripurasundari. The goddess is housed in a separate shrine inside the Temple complex. This temple is one of the Three Sakthi Temples in the region. Thiruvudai Amman, Melur is known as Ichchaa Sakthi (the one who fulfills wishes); Vadivudai Amman, Tiruvottiyur is known as Gnaana Sakthi (the one who blesses with Gananam) and the Kodiyidai Amman Temple, Thirumullaivoyal as Kriyaa Sakthi (the one who assists us in all our actions).\n\nOther deities  present in the temple include Agasalingam,  Thiruvotrieswarar, Thiruptheeswarar(between Vattaparaiman and Durga shrines), Kuzhandhai Eesar, Kalyana sundarar, Jaganadhar, Annamalayar, Ramanathar, Suryan, Chandran, Nalvars, Jambukeswarar, Nagalingar, [[Meenakshi]], Sundareswarar, Sagasralingam, Amirthakandeesar, Gowlieeswarar, and [[Ekapada|Ekapaadhar]], Gunalaya Vinayagar, Aruljothi Murugan, Valar Kali. The twenty seven stars of Tamil calendar are believed to have worshipped Shiva in this temple.\n\nThe inscription park at the temple has about 20 inscriptions from the time of the Chola kings installed.<ref name=\"InscriptionsInBadState\"/>\n\n==Thyagaraja Cult==\n[[File:Somaskanda thirunageswaram.jpg|200px|right|thumb|Somaskand image, associated with the Thyagaraja cult]]\nThough the presiding deity of the temple is Adipuriswarar, the temple is closely associated with the Thyagaraja cult of [[Saivism]].{{sfn|Ghose| 1996| p= 146}} [[Somaskanda]] is the iconic form of Thyagaraja and is believed to have emerged from the 10th century, the period coinciding [[Raja Raja Chola]].{{sfn|Ghose| 1996| p= 24}}  The 8th-century saint [[Sundarar]] is believed to have spread the cult from [[Thyagaraja Temple, Tiruvarur|Tiruvarur]] to the temple here.{{sfn|Ghose| 1996| p= 146}} The Lord tricked him by making him take a vow that he would never leave Tiruvottriyur, but he breaks the promise and becomes blind.{{sfn|Ghose| 1996| p= 146}} The Lord of Tiruvottriyur and Tiruvarur are the same in terms of religious experience, but on the pilgrim tradition, Tiruvottriyur is affronted because Sundarar abandons and goes back to Tiruvarur.{{sfn|Ghose| 1996| p= 146}} The event is celebrated every year in the temple.{{sfn|Ghose| 1996| p= 146}}\n\nThe seven dance forms of Thyagaraja, the ''Sapthavitankam'', is represented in the cultic network comprising [[Thyagaraja Temple, Tiruvarur|Thyagarajar Temple]] in [[Tiruvarur]], [[Dharbaranyeswarar Temple]] in [[Tirunallar]], [[Kayarohanaswami Temple, Nagapattinam|Kayarohanaswamy Temple]] in [[Nagapattinam]],  [[Kannayariamudayar Temple, Thirukkarayil|Kannayariamudayar Temple]] in Thirukarayil, [[Brahmapureeswarar Temple, Thirukkuvalai|Brahmapureeswarar Temple]] in [[Thirukkuvalai]], [[Vaimoornathar Temple, Tiruvaimur|Vaimoornaathar Temple]] in Tiruvaimur and [[Vedaranyeswarar Temple]] in [[Vedaranyam]].{{sfn|Ghose| 1996| p= 64}} The Tiruvottiyur temple is placed at the centre of a similar network comprising [[Marundeeswarar Temple]] in [[Tiruvanmiyur]], Accalpuram in [[Sirkali]] and Tirukachoor near [[Singaperumalkoil]], treated closest to the myth of Tiruvarur.{{sfn|Ghose| 1996| p= 64}} Both the Tiruvarur and Tiruvottriyur temples are believed to have the same dance poses by Shiva, as asserted by ''Tiruvorriyurpuranam''.{{sfn|Ghose| 1996| pp= 89-90}} The dance pattern of the temple is called ''Padamanatanam'', a continuation of Tiruvarur temple - [[Vishnu]] is believed to have gone berserk and missed the dance at Tiruvarur, and Thyagaraja asked him to go to Tiruvottriyur where he said he promised to perform the same dance.{{sfn|Ghose| 1996| pp= 99-100}}\n\n== Literary mention ==\nThe temple is reverred in the verses of ''[[Tevaram]]'', the 7th century saivite canonical work by the three saint poets namely, [[Appar]], [[Sundarar]] and  [[Sambandar]].\n\n:::\"\u0bb5\u0bc6\u0bb3\u0bcd\u0bb3\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc8\u0b9a\u0bcd \u0b9a\u0b9f\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0bb5\u0bc8\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4 \u0bb5\u0bc7\u0ba4\u0b95\u0bc0 \u0ba4\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0bb1\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bbe\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bcd\n::: \u0bae\u0bc6\u0bb3\u0bcd\u0bb3\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbe \u0ba9\u0b9f\u0bc8\u0baf \u0bb5\u0bc7\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bc6\u0baf\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bb0\u0bc1 \u0b9e\u0bbe\u0ba9\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bc0\u0baf\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bcd\n::: \u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd\u0bb3\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bb4\u0bbf\u0baf \u0ba8\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0bb1\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbe\u0baf\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bb2\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0ba8\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0bb1\u0bc1\n::: \u0b89\u0bb3\u0bcd\u0bb3\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0bb3\u0bca\u0bb3\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bc1 \u0bae\u0bbe\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0bae\u0bca\u0bb1\u0bcd\u0bb1\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bc2 \u0bb0\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bc8\u0baf \u0b95\u0bcb\u0bb5\u0bc7.\"\ntranslating to\n:::\"People of this world!\n::: if you want to reach the feet of the Lord who sang the V\u0113tams and who placed the flood of the Ka\u1e45kai on his head,\n:::patiently listen to the way by which you can attain them.\n::: being united in the body of those who have burnt with the help of the fire of spiritual wisdom which grants the ultimate reality, all evil thoughts.\n::: the king of O\u1e5f\u1e5fiy\u016br is the light in the hearts of such people\".{{sfn|Fourth Thirumurai|2004}}\nThe temple was the home of the Hindu saint [[Pattinathar]]{{sfn|Hurd| 2010| p= 37}} and the location where he attained ''[[samadhi]]'' in the form of a ''[[lingam]]''. It is the birthplace of [[Kaliya Nayanar]], one of the 63 [[Nayanars]]. This temple of yore finds a definitive place in Tamil Saivite history as this is the place where the Marriage of Sree Gnanasambandar was supposed to happen but concluded in Sree Gnanasambandar being absorbed with several others into the jyothi before the marriage could be solemnised. The Carnatic composer [[Tyagaraja]] visited this temple{{sfn|Hurd| 2010| p= 37}} and composed the Thiruvottiyur Pancharatna or 5 Gems in praise of the Goddess Sree Tripurasundari.  ''Tiruvorriyur Mummanikovai'' is a work in praise of the deity in the temple.{{sfn|Murdoch| 1865| pp= 92-93}} ''Tiruvorriyur Antathi'' is a 19th-century work by Gnanasampathavaran in praise of the deity of the temple.{{sfn|Murdoch| 1865| pp= 92-93}} ''Tiruvorriyur Moovar Tamil'' is an extract of ''Tevaram'' specific to the temple. ''Tiruvorriyur  Nadana Sarithram'' is a historic depiction of dance in the temple{{sfn|Murdoch| 1865| pp= 92-93}} ''Vadivudaiampal Asiriyavirutham'' by Rama Mudaliar, ''Vadivudaiamman Kummipadal'', ''Vadivudaiamman Navarattinam'' and ''Vadivudaiamman Panssarathinam'' by Kanniappa Uvattiyayar are 19th century works glorifying Vadivudaiamman, the prime consort of the primary deity of the temple.{{sfn|Murdoch| 1865| p= 97}}\n\nThe Nineteenth century Saint Shri Ramalinga Adigalar was a daily visitor to this temple during his younger days and has sung many poems in praise of this Lord. The other important Saint associated with this temple is Shri Topeswamy.\n\n==Festivals==\nThe prime festival is performed in the Tamil month of Masi (February\u2013March){{sfn|Bhargava|Bhatt| 2006| p= 457}}{{sfn|Rasheed |1907| p= 255}} and historically draws large crowd.{{sfn|Imperial Gazetteer of India:Volume 17 |1908| p= 563}} On the eighth day, an additional function called Mahiladisevai is performed.{{sfn|Bhargava|Bhatt| 2006| p= 457}} The Durgadevi shrine in the northern side of the temple is associated with [[Kannagi]], the protagonist of ''[[Silappadikaram]]'', a 2nd-century Tamil epic.{{sfn|Madras Tercentenary Celebration Committee|1994| p= 357}} Each year a 15-day festival is celebrated in honour of Durga Devi and on the last day, the thatch roof of the event is burnt to symbolize Kannagi burning Madurai at the end of the epic.{{sfn|Madras Tercentenary Celebration Committee|1994| p= 357}}{{sfn|Rasheed |1907| p= 255}}\n\n==Temple administration==\nDuring 1786 to 1831 CE, there were frequent clashes between the right-hand castes comprising handicraft people and poor and the left-hand castes comprising wealthy and parsimonious merchants.{{sfn|Mukund |2005| pp= 81-85}}{{sfn|Brimnes|1999| pp= 81-83}} It was the practise of British administrators to bestow the office of chief administrator of the temple to rich merchants. Following the custom, Lingi Chetti headed from 1754 CE,{{sfn|Mukund |2005| pp= 81-85}} and after his death, his family inherited the post. The right-hand caste people were highly irritated that the post was inherited by the left-hand caste. In August 1786, the left-hand caste submitted a petition to the Governor and the council of Fort St. George claiming the right-hand caste had no right over the administration of the temple and were indulged in attack of one of the left-hand person.{{sfn|Mukund |2005| pp= 81-85}}{{sfn|Brimnes|1999| pp= 81-83}} The English sidestepped by ruling that both had liberty to perform their ceremonies according to the respective customs. It was also announced that the heads of each would be responsible for offenders. While the left-hand caste abided by the order, the right-hand caste stopped their practises. There were intermittent clashes initiated by both the parties and once resulted in attacking the sepoys involved in protection.{{sfn|Brimnes|1999| pp= 81-83}} The dissension cropped once more during 1828 when the officiating priest complained about the chief administrator.{{sfn|Mukund |2005| pp= 81-85}} In 1831, there were renewed complaints against the chief administrator over the authority of dancing girls and his right in administering the temple stating financial irregularity.{{sfn|Mukund |2005| pp= 81-85}} The dancing girls were immediately removed from the temple. The collector upheld the action against the dancing girls and ruled that Arunachala Chetti of the left-hand would be the rightful administrator of the temple. It also suggested to the right-hand caste that no complaints would be entertained unless specific instances were shown where the right-hand moved away from customs.{{sfn|Mukund |2005| pp= 81-85}}\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|India|Hinduism}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|3}}\n* {{cite web|title=Fourth Thirumurai|url=http://www.thevaaram.org/en/thirumurai_1/songview.php?thiru=4&Song_idField=4045&padhi=113+&button=Please+go|publisher=thevaaram.org|accessdate = 2012-06-18|ref={{sfnRef|Fourth Thirumurai|2004}} }}\n* {{cite book|title=Ancient India|section=Educational Institutions (B.C. 200- A.D. 700)|editor-last=Iyer|editor-first=Shymala M.|publisher=Publications Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Government of India|location=New Delhi|last=Tyagi|first=Anil Kumar|year=2013|pages=|isbn=978-81-230-1896-6|ref={{sfnRef|Tyagi, 2013|pp=140\u2013144}}}}\n* {{Citation |last=Ayyar |first=P. V. Jagadisa |title=South Indian shrines: illustrated |year=1991 |publisher=Asian Educational Services |location=New Delhi |isbn=81-206-0151-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NLSGFW1uZboC&pg=PA42&dq=tiruvorriyur&hl=en&sa=X&ei=gXziT4bDHonk9ASOqvSHCA&ved=0CDwQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=tiruvorriyur&f=false|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | title=Land and people of Indian states and union territories. 25. Tamil Nadu| last=Bhargava| first=Gopal K. |first2=Shankarlal C. |last2=Bhatt |year=2006| publisher=Kalpaz Publications|location=Delhi|url=https://books.google.com/boo