#v=onepage&q=tiruvottiyur%20temple&f=false|isbn=978-1-4134-3843-7|ref=harv}}.\n* {{Cite book|title=Imperial Gazetteer of India:Volume 17: Provincial Series|pages=561\u2013562|last=Imperial Gazetteer of India:Volume 17|accessdate=2009-10-20|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ngK2AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA561&dq=tiruvottiyur+temple&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Bl3iT8fGDIGm8QSMipCGCA&ved=0CF4Q6AEwBjgK#v=onepage&q=tiruvottiyur%20temple&f=false|year=1908|ref=harv}}\n* {{Citation |last=Kamath|first=Rina |title=Chennai |year=2000|publisher=Orient Longman Limited |location=Chennai|isbn=9788125013785|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bw2vDg2fTrMC&pg=PA19&dq=tiruvottiyur+temple&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Bl3iT8fGDIGm8QSMipCGCA&ved=0CE0Q6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=tiruvottiyur%20temple&f=false|ref=harv}}\n* {{Citation |last=Madras Tercentenary Celebration Committee|first= |title=The Madras Tercentenary Commemoration Volume |year=1994 |publisher=Asian Educational Services |location=New Delhi |isbn=81-206-0537-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pwMk4FIcpuUC&pg=PA333&dq=parthasarathy+temple&hl=en&sa=X&ei=pCjdT-GoK4mW8gTc0tiFCw&ved=0CD0Q6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=parthasarathy%20temple&f=false|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=Temples in South India|last=V.|first=Meena|publisher=Harikumar Arts|location=Kanniyakumari|year=1974|edition=1st|page=|ref={{sfnRef|Meena, 1974}}}}\n* {{Citation |last=Mukund|first=Kanakalatha |title=The View from Below: Indigenous Society, Temples, and the Early Colonial State in Tamil Nadu 1700-1835|year=2005|publisher=Orient Longman Private Limited|location=Hyderabad |isbn=81-250-2800-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5BMljBxJXtoC&pg=PA81&dq=tiruvottiyur+temple&hl=en&sa=X&ei=cAjhT6O5DYe88ASr3PmRDQ&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=left-hand&f=false|ref=harv}}\n* {{Citation |last=Murdoch|first=John|title=Classified Catalogue of Tamil Printed Books with introductory notices|year=1865|publisher=Christian Vernacular Education Society|location=Madras |isbn=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YaY-AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA93&dq=tiruvorriyur&hl=en&sa=X&ei=vaXjT82TM4SG8QTrhZjwCQ&ved=0CEsQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=tiruvorriyur&f=false|ref=harv}}\n* {{Citation |last=Rasheed|first=Abdur|title=The travellers' companion: containing a brief description of places of pilgrimage and important towns in India|year=1907|publisher=Railway Board|location=Calcutta |isbn=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fRQiAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA253&dq=tiruvottiyur+temple&hl=en&sa=X&ei=pljiT8KjOYyI8QTw1tSGCA&ved=0CG8Q6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=tiruvottiyur%20temple&f=false|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0zlOCJ6B95c Reason for the name]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6JSDr-VFpLc  Devaradiyar honoured @Thiruvotriyur]\n\n{{Chennai Topics}}\n{{Places of worship in Chennai}}\n{{Worship in Hinduism}}\n{{List of Hindu temples in Tamil Nadu}}\n{{Famous Shiva temples}}\n{{HinduMythology}}\n\n[[Category:Padal Petra Stalam]]\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Chennai]]\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Tiruvallur district]]\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLiterary mention:clean up,MOS:HEADCAPS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thyagaraja_Temple,_Tiruvottiyur"}
{"title_page": "C. K. Hansen", "text_new": "'''C. K. Hansen''' was a [[Denmark|Danish]] wholesale company and [[Freight forwarder|non-vessel operating common carrier]] established in 1856 at [[Esplanaden, Copenhagen|Esplanaden]] 15 in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. The subsidiary '''Dampskibsselskabet Dannebrog''' was established in 1893. The company's former headquarters at Esplanaden 15&mdash;a [[Neoclassical architecture|Late Neoclassical]] building from 1856 designed by [[Gustav Friedrich Hetsch]]&mdash;was listed on the [[Listed buildings in \u00d8sterbro|Danish registry of protected buildings and places]].\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Esplanaden painting.jpg|thumb|200px|C. K. Hansen's building at Toldbodvej 15]]\nC. K. Hansen was founded on 13 July 1856 by Christian Kjellerup Hansen (1813-1868). Hansen had previously worked for J. B. Suhr & Co.<ref name=\"DBL\">{{cite web|url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Dansk_Biografisk_Leksikon/Handel_og_industri/Grosserer/C.K._Hansen|title=C. K. Hansen|language=Danish|website=[[Dansk Biografisk Leksikon]]|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\nHansen's son [[Johan Hansen (1838\u20131913)|Johan Hansen]] was in 1857 made a partner in the company. Johan Hansen was after his father's death in 1868 joined by Oluf Hansen. Johan Hansen's sons, Johan and Robert Hansen, were made partners in the company following Oluf Hansen's death in 1897.<ref name=\"coneliand\">{{cite web|url=http://www.coneliand.dk/Danmarks%20aeldste%20forretninger/DAEF%20200-299/Side%20218%20Hans%20-%20Hans.html|title=C. K. Hansen|language=Danish|website=coneliand.dk|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nC. K. Hansen was in 1950 owned by C. J. C. Harhoff (born 1886), Knud Hansen (born 1892), Bennet C. K. Hansen (born 1914) and Preben Harhoff.<ref name=\"coneliand\"/>\n\n===Subsidiaries===\nThe shipping company Dampskibsselskabet Dannebrog was established as a subsidiary in 1883. It was in 1915 merged with Dampskibsselskabet af 1896 (founded 1896) and Dampskibsselskabet Neptun (founded 1901). The company's coal business was in 1912 separated from the parent company under the name A/S K\u00f8benhavns Bunkerkul Depot. Another subsidiary, K\u00f8benhavns Stevedore Comp, was in 1943 created from the company's [[stevedore|stevedore business]].<ref name=\"coneliand\"/>\n\n==Building==\nC. K. Hansen was based at Toldbodvej 15 (now Esplanaden 15). The building was constructed in 1856 to a [[Neoclassical architecture|Late Neoclassical]] design by [[Gustav Friedrich Hetsch]]. It was part of Hetsch's masterplan which was to give the entire [[Nordre Toldbod]] and Toldbodvej area a face lift. The project was never completed but [[Lumskebugten]] and the Lion's Gate were also designed by Hetsch as part of the masterplan. The building was listed on the [[Listed buildings in \u00d8sterbro|Danish registry of protected buildings and places]] in 1970.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kulturarv.dk/fbb/sagvis.pub?sag=3100576|title=Sag: Esplanaden 15-17|language=Danish|website=Kulturstyrelsen|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dannebrog Rederi]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [Afbildet p\u00e5 P. S. Kr\u00f8yers mal., Fra Kbh.s B\u00f8rs, 1895 (B\u00f8rsen) Source]\n\n[[Category:Defunct companies of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Wholesalers of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Danish companies established in 1856]]\n[[Category:Listed buildings and structures in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1856]]\n", "text_old": "'''C. K. Hansen''' was a [[Denmark|Danish]] wholesale company and [[Freight forwarder|non-vessel operating common carrier]] established in 1856 at [[Esplanaden, Copenhagen|Esplanaden]] 15 in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. The subsidiary '''Dampskibsselskabet Dannebrog''' was established in 1893. The company's former headquarters at Esplanaden 15&mdash;a [[Neoclassical architecture|Late Neoclassical]] building from 1856 designed by [[Gustav Friedrich Hetsch]]&mdash;was listed on the [[Listed buildings in \u00d8sterbro|Danish registry of protected buildings and places]].\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Esplanaden painting.jpg|thumb|200px|C. K. Hansen's building at Toldbodvej 15]]\nC. K. Hansen was founded on 13 July 1856 by Christian Kjellerup Hansen (1813-1868). Hansen had previously worked for J. B. Suhr & Co.<ref name=\"DBL\">{{cite web|url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Dansk_Biografisk_Leksikon/Handel_og_industri/Grosserer/C.K._Hansen|title=C. K. Hansen|language=Danish|website=[[Dansk Biografisk Leksikon]]|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\nHansen's son [[Johan Hansen (1838\u20131913)|Johan Hansen]] was in 1857 made a partner in the company. Johan Hansen was after his father's death in 1868 joined by Oluf Hansen. Johan Hansen's sons, Johan and Robert Hansen, were made partners in the company following Oluf Hansen's death in 1897.<ref name=\"coneliand\">{{cite web|url=http://www.coneliand.dk/Danmarks%20aeldste%20forretninger/DAEF%20200-299/Side%20218%20Hans%20-%20Hans.html|title=C. K. Hansen|language=Danish|website=coneliand.dk|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nC. K. Hansen was in 1950 owned by C. J. C. Harhoff (born 1886), Knud Hansen (born 1892), Bennet C. K. Hansen (born 1914) and Preben Harhoff.<ref name=\"coneliand\"/>\n\n===Subsidaries===\nThe shipping company Dampskibsselskabet Dannebrog was established as a subsidiary in 1883. It was in 1915 merged with Dampskibsselskabet af 1896 (founded 1896) and Dampskibsselskabet Neptun (founded 1901). The company's coal business was in 1912 separated from the parent company under the name A/S K\u00f8benhavns Bunkerkul Depot. Another subsidiary, K\u00f8benhavns Stevedore Comp, was in 1943 created from the company's [[ stevedore|stevedore business]].<ref name=\"coneliand\"/>\n\n==Building==\nC. K. Hansen was based at Toldbodvej 15 (now Esplanaden 15). The building was constructed in 1856 to a [[Neoclassical architecture|Late Neoclassical]] design by [[Gustav Friedrich Hetsch]]. It was part of Hetsch's masterplan which was to give the entire [[Nordre Toldbod]] and Toldbodvej area a face lift. The project was never completed but [[Lumskebugten]] and the Lion's Gate were also designed by Hetsch as part of the masterplan. The building was listed on the [[Listed buildings in \u00d8sterbro|Danish registry of protected buildings and places]] in 1970.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kulturarv.dk/fbb/sagvis.pub?sag=3100576|title=Sag: Esplanaden 15-17|language=Danish|website=Kulturstyrelsen|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dannebrog Rederi]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [Afbildet p\u00e5 P. S. Kr\u00f8yers mal., Fra Kbh.s B\u00f8rs, 1895 (B\u00f8rsen) Source]\n\n[[Category:Defunct companies of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Wholesalers of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Danish companies established in 1856]]\n[[Category:Listed buildings and structures in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1856]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: Subsidaries \u2192 Subsidiaries", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C._K._Hansen"}
{"title_page": "Stephen Boyd", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Stephen Boyd\n| image        = Stephen Boyd.jpg\n| caption      = Boyd in 1961\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1931|07|04|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Glengormley]], [[County Antrim]], Northern Ireland\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1977|06|02|1931|07|04|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Northridge, Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n| birth_name   = William Millar\n| years_active = 1950\u20131977\n| occupation   = Actor\n| resting_place = [[Oakwood Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n| partner   = [[Marisa Mell]] (1970-1972)\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Mariella di Sarzana<br>|1958|1959|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Elizabeth Mills<br>| 1974|1977|end=his death}}\n}}\n\n'''Stephen Boyd''' (4 July 1931&nbsp;\u2013 2 June 1977) was a [[Northern Irish]] actor. A native of [[Glengormley]], [[County Antrim]],<ref name=bbc>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-12135044 \"Stephen Boyd: The Busker Who Became a Screen Idol\"] BBC News; retrieved 14 April 2014.</ref> Boyd appeared in some 60 films, most notably as the villainous Messala in ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]'' (1959), a role that earned him the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]]. He received his second  [[Golden Globe Award]] nomination for ''[[Billy Rose's Jumbo]]'' (1962). He also appeared, sometimes as a hero and sometimes as a malefactor, in the major big-screen productions ''[[The Night Heaven Fell|Les bijoutiers du clair de lune]]'' (1958), ''[[The Bravados]]'' (1958), ''[[Imperial Venus (film)|Imperial Venus]]'' (1962), ''[[The Fall of the Roman Empire (film)|The Fall of the Roman Empire]]'' (1964), ''[[Genghis Khan (1965 film)|Genghis Khan]]'' (1965), ''[[Fantastic Voyage]]'' (1966) and ''[[Shalako (film)|Shalako]]'' (1968).\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\nStephen Boyd \u2013 real name William Millar \u2013 was born in a house, long since demolished, at the corner of the Doagh Road, Whitehouse on 4 July 1931.<ref>[http://daggy.name/cop/bkofdead/99999989.htm Profile], daggy.name/cop/bkofdead; accessed 28 June 2014.</ref> Boyd was the youngest of nine siblings born to Irish/Canadian parents, James Alexander Millar and his wife Martha Boyd. At a very early age, William, or Billy as he was known, moved with the family to live in Glengormley. Boyd attended the local Public Elementary School and [[Ballyclare High School]], but at the age of fourteen Boyd quit school to take up other jobs to help support his family. He eventually joined the Ulster Group Theatre where he learned the behind the scenes tasks of the theatre. He became well known in Belfast for his contributions as a gravel-voiced policeman on the Ulster Radio program \"The McCooeys\", the story of a Belfast family written by Joseph Tomelty.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''The Journal News - White Plains New York, 09 Jul 1969''</ref><ref name=\"newsletter.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/blue-plaque-honour-for-ulster-born-hollywood-star-stephen-boyd-1-8552887|title=Blue plaque honour for Ulster-born Hollywood star Stephen Boyd|publisher=}}</ref> Boyd eventually worked his way up to character parts and then starring roles. By nineteen he had toured Canada with summer stock companies. In 1950 he made a coast to coast tour of America with the [[Clare Tree Major]] Company,<ref>''Stephen Boyd, The Man Who Never Wants to Pour Another Coffee, by John Neal''</ref> 1956 performing ''[[A Streetcar Named Desire]]'' <ref>''Daily News, NY, NY May 5, 1963''</ref> in the lead role as [[Stanley Kowalski]]. Boyd would later recall this as \"the best performance I ever gave in my life\". <ref>''Movieland Magazine interview December of 1962''</ref>\n\nBy the time he was twenty, Boyd had a wide range of theatre experience, but he longed for the big stage.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">''Movie Screen'' Stephen Boyd Interview, June 1960</ref> In 1952 Boyd moved to London and worked in a cafeteria and busked outside a cinema in Leicester Square to get money as he was literally close to starvation.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Boyd caught his first break as a doorman at the Odeon Theatre. The Leicester Square Cinema across the street recruited him to usher attendees during the British Academy Awards in the early 1950s. During the awards ceremony he was noticed by actor Sir [[Michael Redgrave]], who used his connections to introduce Boyd to the director of the Windsor Repertory Group.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> At this point Boyd's stage career in the U.K. began to flourish with performances in \"The Deep Blue Sea\" and \"Barnett's Folly\" <ref>''Movieland'' Magazine, December 1962</ref>\n\n===Early roles===\nBoyd's first role which brought him acclaim<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2194&dat=19560405&id=X7cxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dOQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=7080,904122&hl=en |title=Irish-Canadian Film Actor Gains Stardom in Big Part |newspaper=Ottawa Citizen |page=28 |date=5 April 1956 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> was as an Irish spy in the movie ''[[The Man Who Never Was]]'', based on the book by [[Ewen Montagu]]. The movie was released in April 1956.\n\nShortly thereafter he signed a ten-year contract with [[20th Century Fox]] studios,<ref>''Hedda Hopper, Los Angeles Times, May 29, 1956''</ref> who began prepping him for Hollywood. But it would be a while until Boyd actually set foot on a Hollywood back-lot. Boyd's next stop was Portugal to make ''[[A Hill in Korea]]'', which also featured future stars [[Michael Caine]] and [[Robert Shaw (British actor)|Robert Shaw]].<ref>Michael Caine, ''What's it all About?'', page 114-115</ref> In June 1956, Boyd was cast in the nautical, ship-wreck adventure ''[[Seven Waves Away|Abandon Ship!]]'' for Columbia Studios starring [[Tyrone Power]]. This was filmed in the summer of 1956 in London where the British Navy  built a huge 35,000 gallon water tank for the movie.<ref>''St. Louis Dispatch'' 14 July 1956</ref>\n\nIn November 1956, for Twentieth Century Fox, Boyd traveled to the [[British West Indies]] as part of a large ensemble cast in [[Darryl Zanuck]]'s racially provocative film ''[[Island in the Sun (film)|Island in the Sun]] starring [[Dorothy Dandridge]]'', based on the [[Alec Waugh]] novel.<ref>''The Corpus Christi Caller, Nov 27, 1956''</ref> Boyd portrayed a young English aristocrat who becomes the lover of [[Joan Collins]]. Boyd would be loaned out to the [[J. Arthur Rank]] production of ''[[Seven Thunders (film)|Seven Thunders]] (Beast of Marseilles)'', a [[World War II]] romance set in Nazi-occupied Marseilles.<ref>''The Los Angeles Times, March 23, 1957''</ref> This movie was filmed on location in [[Marseilles]] and at [[Pinewood Studios]] in London in the spring of 1957 <ref>''https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0050174/locations?ref_=tt_dt_dt''</ref>  and featured Boyd in his most prominent starring film role yet.\n\nAround the same time French actress [[Brigitte Bardot]] was given the opportunity to cast her own leading man in her next movie after her success in [[Roger Vadim]]'s ''[[And God Created Woman (1956 film)|And God Created Woman]]'', and she chose Boyd.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1301&dat=19580504&id=g3dWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8eQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3095,1129485&hl=en |last=Lambert |first=John |title=Bardot Picks a Co-Star |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=4 May 1958 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> From August to October 1957,<ref>''Philadelphia Inquirer August 29, 1957''</ref> Bardot, Boyd and [[Alida Valli]] filmed the lusty romance ''[[The Night Heaven Fell]]'', directed by [[Roger Vadim]] in Paris and in the region of [[M\u00e1laga]], [[Spain]], specifically the small, white-washed town of Mijas.<ref>''Ottawa Citizen Feb 15, 1958''</ref> Being in the Bardot spotlight added much to Boyd's film credit, in addition to bringing him notice in Hollywood.<ref>The Salt Lake Tribune, 24 June 1958,  ''Ireland's Boyd- A Man Apart&nbsp;\u2014 And all Because of Bardot''</ref>\n\nStephen Boyd finally arrived in Hollywood in January 1958 to take on his first true Hollywood role as the leader of a quartet of renegade outlaws in the Twentieth Century Fox western ''[[The Bravados]]'', which starred [[Gregory Peck]] and [[Joan Collins]]. Even though this was a Hollywood production, the actual filming took place in [[Morelia]], Mexico.<ref>''Lee Belser, Lubbock Evening Journal, February 28, 1958''</ref>\n\n===''Ben-Hur''===\nAfter the filming of ''[[The Bravados]]'' was complete in late March 1958, Stephen Boyd returned to Hollywood to audition for the coveted role of Messala in [[MGM]]'s upcoming epic ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]''. Many other actors, including [[Victor Mature]], [[Kirk Douglas]], [[Leslie Nielsen]] and [[Stewart Granger]] had been considered for the part,<ref>''The Los Angeles Times, April 17, 1958''</ref> but Stephen Boyd's screen test convinced director [[William Wyler]] that he had found the perfect villain for his epic, as Wyler had also admired Boyd's performance in ''[[The Man Who Never Was]]'' the previous year. Boyd was hurried off to join actor [[Charlton Heston]] in Rome in May 1958 to learn the chariot racing aspect of his role. Heston had already been practicing behind the chariot for weeks, so Boyd needed to learn quickly. Boyd was also required to wear brown contact lenses as Messala, which irritated his eyes and caused vision problems for a few months after the movie was completed. Despite this, Boyd described the filming experience of ''Ben-Hur'' (which took place in [[Cinecitt\u00e0]] Studios in Rome), as the most exciting experience of his life.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19581204&id=zjkxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5wAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7405,6177173&hl=en |title=Stephen Boyd Endures Agony for Art's Sake |last=Heffernan |first=Harold |newspaper=Toledo Blade |date=4 December 1958 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nYears after the movie was released, interim ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]'' screenwriter and novelist [[Gore Vidal]] revealed that Boyd had portrayed his famous character [[Messala (Ben-Hur)|Messala]] in ''Ben-Hur'' with an underlying homosexual energy, as instructed to by [[Gore Vidal]] when he greets Ben-Hur [[Charlton Heston]] in the opening sequence. In Gore Vidal's autobiography \"Palimpsest,\"<ref name=\"Gore Vidal pages 303\">''Palimpsest by Gore Vidal, pages 303 to 307, published in 1996''</ref> Vidal describes his discussion first with director [[William Wyler]], concerning Messala's underlying motivation, namely that Messala and Judah Ben-Hur had previously been lovers.  This was based on an idea by Vidal to enhance the tension between the two main antagonists. Wyler specifically told Vidal, \"You talk to Boyd. But don't ''you'' say a word to Chuck or he'll fall apart.\" <ref>(Palimpsest, by Gore Vidal, Page 306)</ref> In \"Palimpsest\", Vidal said, \"Over the next few years, whenever we met (William Wyler), we quarreled amiably over what I had put in the scene and what Steven Boyd is clearly playing.\"  Vidal would later come into conflict with actor [[Charlton Heston]] about his version of the Messala/Ben-Hur relationship and the implications surrounding [[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]].<ref name=\"Gore Vidal pages 303\"/>\n\nAfter the filming of ''Ben-Hur'' was completed Boyd returned to Hollywood in early 1959 to star with [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] winner [[Susan Hayward]] in the Canadian-based drama ''[[Woman Obsessed]]''. Some advertisements for this movie labeled Boyd as \"The New Gable.\"<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19580812&id=TAUkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4QAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7250,1107861&hl=en ''Toledo Blade''] 12 August 1958</ref>  He was then part of another excellent ensemble cast in the adaptation of [[Rona Jaffe]]'s novel ''[[The Best of Everything (film)|The Best of Everything]]'', filmed in May and June 1959 at Fox Studios in Hollywood and on location in New York City.\n\n[[File:Stephen Boyd in Ben Hur trailer.jpg|thumb|From the trailer for the film ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]'' (1959).]]\n\n''Ben-Hur'' was released in December 1959 and immediately made Boyd an international star. His portrayal of the Roman tribune Messala brought in rave reviews. Press columnist Erskine Johnson wrote, \"A brass hat and the armor of a Roman warrior in ''Ben-Hur'' does for Stephen Boyd what a tight dress does for Marilyn Monroe.\"<ref>''The Odessa American'', 19 December 1959, \"Actor Stephen Boyd Really Packs Wallop\"</ref> Ruth Waterbury, in her Boyd feature in the Pittsburgh Post Gazette, would describe Boyd's character as \"the dangerously masculine and quite magnificent Messala.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1129&dat=19610715&id=P8daAAAAIBAJ&sjid=NmwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4358,3443168&hl=en |title=Boydie |last=Waterbury |first=Ruth |newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |date=15 July 1961 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> ''Modern Screen'' magazine in 1960 stated that Boyd's  ruthless Messala had \"lost the chariot race but captured the sympathy and sex appeal of ''Ben-Hur''.\"<ref>''Modern Screen'', Stephen Boyd \"Introducing the Sensational Star of Ben Hur and Best of Everything\", October\u2013December 1960</ref>\n\n===1960s===\nBoyd was featured in the popular TV program ''[[This Is Your Life]]'' on 3 February 1960, which featured many of Boyd's family members and acquaintances (including Michael Redgrave) telling stories about his early life and film career. This should be some indication of how \"Stephen Boyd fever\" was catching. Newspaper columnists were getting swarmed with letters from female fans of all ages wanting to know more about Boyd.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19600309&id=sQcvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bE4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=7562,2549137&hl=en \"Maids, Matrons Here Cheering For Stephen Boyd\"] ''Pittsburgh Press'' 9 March 1960</ref> He was being sent dozens of starring roles, most of which he had to turn down due to other obligations. He opted out of the biblical epic ''[[The Story of Ruth]]'', which didn't please Fox studios, and he was one of the front-runners to star with [[Marilyn Monroe]] in her picture ''Let's Make Love''.<ref>''The News Review'' 24 March 1960, \"Oscar Ground Rules Hazy For Supporting Actor Roles\"</ref>\n\nIn early 1960 Boyd won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]] for his performance in ''Ben-Hur''.<ref name=\"IMDb profile\">[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000963/bio IMDb profile], imdb.com; accessed 28 June 2014.</ref> In January 1960 Boyd made a guest appearance alongside the silent-era ''Ben-Hur'' stars [[Ramon Novarro]] and [[Francis X. Bushman]] on [[Hedda Hopper]]'s special television programme ''Hedda Hopper's Hollywood''.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1356&dat=19600108&id=Q3hhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3wQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6554,1304721&hl=en \"Hedda Hopper's Show on Sunday\"] ''Ocala Star Banner'', 8 January 1960</ref> In February 1960 he starred in the [[Playhouse 90]] television performance called ''The Sound of Trumpets'' with [[Dolores Hart]], which garnered good reviews. He also appeared as a singing guest on [[The Dinah Shore Chevy Show]] on 13 March 1960 where he performed two Irish folk songs with Dinah Shore, \"The Leprechaun Song\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.traditionalmusic.co.uk/irish-songs-ballads-lyrics/leprechaun_song.htm|title=Irish Music, Song and Ballad Lyrics for: Leprechaun Song|website=www.traditionalmusic.co.uk}}</ref> and \"Molly Malone\", and an Irish step dance.<ref>(Arizona Republic, 13 March 1960)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x5d2sdr_dinah-shore-03-13-1960-stephen-boyd-shelley-berman_tv|title=Dinah Shore (03_13_1960) - STEPHEN BOYD, SHELLEY BERMAN - Video Dailymotion|date=24 February 2017|website=Dailymotion}}</ref>\n\nBoyd himself chose to do roles which he felt comfortable in. His next choice was ''[[The Big Gamble (1961 film)|The Big Gamble]]'', which featured [[Darryl F. Zanuck]]'s current paramour and French icon [[Juliette Gr\u00e9co]]. It was filmed on the [[Ivory Coast]] of [[West Africa]], [[Dublin]] and the southern part of France in the spring and summer of 1961. The adventure of making this film almost outdid the adventure in the film itself<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1356&dat=19600801&id=YvkjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4QQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1488,3307578&hl=en |title=Trout Fly With Sequins- That's French Fishing Flair |work=Ocala Star-Banner |page=5 |date=1 August 1960 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=861&dat=19601002&id=sOhHAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LoAMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3018,3351049&hl=en |title=Africa's Most Rabid Film Fans |last=Bacon |first=James |work=[[The Victoria Advocate]] |agency=Associated Press |location=London |page=11 |date=2 October 1960 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> as the crew slept in tents in the jungle that were guarded by natives on parole for cannibalism.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1873&dat=19600925&id=iokeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rswEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2690,3861205&hl=en |title=She Slept with the Cannibals |newspaper=Daytona Beach Morning Journal |page=5C |date=25 September 1960 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>  Boyd nearly drowned in the Ard\u00e8che river during the making of the film. Luckily he was saved by his co-star and excellent swimmer [[David Wayne]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1368&dat=19600705&id=Zl4xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=eg8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2640,2510221&hl=en |title=Wayne Saves Drowning Actor |newspaper=Milwaukee Sentinel |date=5 July 1960 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> Boyd spoke about this incident during his appearance on the popular TV programme ''[[What's My Line?]]'' which aired on 11 December 1960.\n\nBoyd was originally chosen to play [[Mark Antony]] opposite [[Elizabeth Taylor]] in 20th Century Fox's epic production of ''[[Cleopatra (1963 film)|Cleopatra]]'' ([[1963 in film|1963]]) under the direction of [[Rouben Mamoulian]]. He began film work in September 1960 but eventually withdrew from the problem-plagued production after Elizabeth Taylor's severe illness postponed the film for months. (''Cleopatra'' was later directed by [[Joseph L. Mankiewicz]], and the role of Mark Antony went to [[Richard Burton]].)<ref name=\"imdb\">{{IMDb name|0000963}}</ref> During this period of waiting in April 1961 Stephen Boyd was sent to [[Cairo]], Egypt on a publicity tour by [[Twentieth Century Fox]] along with fellow actors [[Julie Newmar]] and [[Barbara Eden]] to attend the inaugural ceremony of the sound and light show at the pyramids of [[Giza]].<ref>''The Los Angeles Times,  13 Apr 1961, Thu,  Page 86''</ref><ref>''Chicago Daily Tribune May 11, 1961''</ref>\n\nAfter several months without active work, Boyd was thrilled to finally get his first post-Cleopatra role.<ref>(The Bridgeport Post, 11 July 1961, \"Stephen Boyd Ends Big Wait\")</ref> The film was ''[[The Inspector (1962 film)|The Inspector]]'', renamed ''Lisa'' for the American release. It was based on the novel by [[Jan de Hartog]] and co- starred actress [[Dolores Hart]]. The film was made in [[Amsterdam]], London and Wales during the summer of 1961. On 9 January 1962, Boyd was featured in a television film from [[General Electric Theater]] called ''The Wall Between'', co-starring [[Ronald Reagan]] and [[Gloria Talbott]].<ref>''The Daily Herald, Provo Utah, 08 January 1962''</ref>  Next, Boyd was again loaned out to MGM Studios to star with [[Doris Day]] in the circus musical ''[[Billy Rose's Jumbo]]'', filmed during the early part of 1962; the role earned Boyd a nomination for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]].\n\nBoyd flew to Rome in the summer of 1962 to act with Italian superstar [[Gina Lollobrigida]] in her long-time pet project ''[[Imperial Venus (film)|Imperial Venus]]'', a romantic epic about the many loves of [[Pauline Bonaparte]], the sister of [[Napoleon]]. This film was the first film to be banned by the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] for male nudity. Boyd appeared in a humorous bedroom scene, naked with only his lower half covered by a bed-sheet.<ref>''Ottawa Citizen'', 10 July 1964, [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2194&dat=19640710&id=Gr0yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Fe0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=1232,2402566&hl=en \"Nude Movie Scenes\u2026How about Lassie?\"]</ref> The suggestion of nudity was too much for the censors and the movie was never released in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19841204&id=qNUvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=CKYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6488,4632441&hl=en |title=Names Etcetera |newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]] |agency=Knight-Ridder |page=30 |date=4 December 1984 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>  Boyd returned to the States briefly after finishing [[Imperial Venus]] where he appeared for the second time on [[The Dinah Shore Chevy Show]], which aired on 11 November 1962. For thus program Boyd was a last minute replacement for actor [[James Garner]] and joined Shore and entertainer [[Dean Martin]] for a few musical numbers.<ref>''Argus Leader (Sioux Falls, South Dakota), November 10, 1962''</ref><ref>''The Times Herald (Port Huron, Michigan), November 10, 1962.''</ref>\n\nBoyd arrived in Spain in early 1963 to begin work on [[Samuel Bronston]]'s massive production of the''[[The Fall of the Roman Empire (film)|The Fall of the Roman Empire]]'', directed by [[Anthony Mann]]. This was filmed during a severely cold winter in Europe and the production in the [[Sierra de Guadarrama]] of Spain encountered several challenges with the snow.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1755&dat=19630205&id=p7gqAAAAIBAJ&sjid=pGUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7159,1061883&hl=en |title=Some Portuguese See Their First Snow |agency=Associated Press |location=London |newspaper=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]] |page=10 |date=5 February 1963 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref><ref>''\"Rome in Madrid\" (1964 Making of The Fall of the Roman Empire film), https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GnWkzdajxwQ''</ref> Boyd's co-star was another Italian legend, Sophia Loren. Boyd also had the opportunity to ride another chariot in this film. Although the movie did well internationally when it was released in April 1964, it was a box office failure in the United States and signaled the end of Roman epics in the 1960s. More appreciated with the passing of time, ''[[The Fall of the Roman Empire (film)|The Fall of the Roman Empire]]'' was also recognized by critics as being a major inspiration for Ridley Scott's [[Academy Award]] winning movie ''[[Gladiator (2000 film)|Gladiator]].''\n<ref>The Fall of the Roman Empire  Film And History by Martin M Winkler, 2009</ref>\n\nBoyd flew back to Hollywood in the summer to star in a [[Bob Hope Presents the Chrysler Theatre]] TV Program with [[Louis Jourdan]] called ''War of Nerves'', which aired on 3 January 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Fjq2oXMBTpc|title=The Chrysler Theater: \"War of Nerves\" (1964)|first=|last=GR160289|date=10 July 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> He then returned to Europe to film the suspenseful ''[[The Third Secret (film)]]'' starring  [[Pamela Franklin]] and [[Diane Cilento]].\n\nOn 23 December 1963, Stephen Boyd became a naturalized U.S. citizen during a ceremony at the Federal Building in Los Angeles, California.<ref>Los Angeles Times, 25 December 1963</ref>\n\nStephen Boyd was originally cast as the lead in Anthony Mann's WWII drama \"''The Unknown Battle''\", which was set to film in early 1964 with co-stars [[Elke Sommer]] and [[Anthony Perkins]] in Norway.<ref>The Los Angeles Times, 24 Jan 1964</ref><ref>The Progress Index, 24 Feb 1964</ref> After several weeks of waiting, studio funding for the project fell through.<ref>Asbury Park Press, 2 July 1964</ref> Boyd sued Mann for $500,000 for a breach of contract, missed time and other lost film opportunities.<ref>Philadelphia Inquirer, 25 April 1964</ref> The project was finally completed by Mann a year later and released as ''[[Heroes of Telemark]]'' with [[Kirk Douglas]] replacing Boyd as the lead.<ref>Looking at Hollywood: Steve Boyd Is Back After Stint Abroad Hopper, Hedda. Chicago Tribune (1963\u2013Current file) [Chicago, Ill] 29 December 1964: b11.</ref>\n\nIn 1964 Boyd continued to make films in Europe, traveling to [[Yugoslavia]] to star as the villain Jamuga in the epic ''[[Genghis Khan (1965 film)|Genghis Khan]]''. Boyd was the top billed and therefore the top paid star in the epic, and this apparently caused friction with up-and-coming star [[Omar Sharif]].<ref>''Miami News'' 25 June 1965, \"More Dramatics than Spectacle in Genghis Khan\"</ref> After completing ''Genghis Khan'', Boyd trekked to [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]] for a brief appearance as the regal King [[Nimrod]] at [[The Tower of Babel]] in [[Dino de Laurentiis]]'s production of ''[[The Bible: In the Beginning...|The Bible]]'', directed by [[John Huston]].<ref>''Chicago Tribune'', 29 December 1964, \"Steve Boyd Is Back After Stint Abroad\"</ref>\n\nAfter all this globe-trotting, the world weary Boyd was very happy to return to the United States to start work on the Twentieth Century Fox science fiction adventure ''[[Fantastic Voyage]]'', co-starring with soon-to-be icon [[Raquel Welch]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1774&dat=19650318&id=3uQhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=oWUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2656,4646021&hl=en |title=Movie Actor Seeks Hollywood Home |agency=UPI |location=Hollywood |work=Sarasota Herald-Tribune |date=18 March 1965 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>  This was filmed in the early part of 1965. In the summer of 1965, Boyd joined German star [[Elke Sommer]] and music legend [[Tony Bennett]] to film the Hollywood drama ''[[The Oscar (film)|The Oscar]]'', based on the eponymous [[Richard Sale (director)|Richard Sale]] novel. The movie was a popular success, but maligned by film critics.<ref>''The Daily Times News'', Burlington North Carolina, 1 August 1966, \"Movie Argument Continues\"</ref> Boyd would make a 10-day visit to [[Iran]] in December 1965 to film his scenes for the [[United Nations]] film project ''[[The Poppy Is Also a Flower]]'',<ref>(Hedda Hopper, Chicago Tribune, 31 December 1965</ref> written by [[James Bond]] creator [[Ian Fleming]].\n\nIn 1966 the producer of ''[[The Oscar (film)|The Oscar]]'', [[Joseph E. Levine|Joseph Levine]], hired Boyd for his next film project, ''[[The Caper of the Golden Bulls]]'', based on a [[William McGivern]] novel. This movie was partly filmed on location in Spain in the summer of 1966. The actors, including Boyd, took part in the famous Feria del Toro de San Fermin festival in [[Pamplona]] (known as the Running of the Bulls).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19660711&id=4TQgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=I1AEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6420,3584537&hl=en |title=Sheilah Graham |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Press]] |page=23 |date=11 July 1966 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nTwo of Boyd's projects were ranked among the top twenty-five grossing films of 1966; ''[[The Bible: In the Beginning...|The Bible]]'' at number one and  ''[[Fantastic Voyage]]'' at twenty.\n\nNext, Boyd starred in a spy thriller ''[[Assignment K]]'' with Swedish model/actress [[Camilla Sparv]], which was filmed in Germany, Austria and London during February and March 1967.<ref>(The Los Angeles Times, 10 January 1967)</ref> Boyd grew a full beard <ref>(Arizona Republic 12 June 1967)</ref> for his next role as the iconic Irish playwright and critic [[George Bernard Shaw]] in the [[Off-Broadway]] play called ''The Bashful Genius'' written by Harold Callen. This was Boyd's first return to the stage since the mid-1950s, and the experience for Boyd was immensely rewarding on a personal level.<ref>(The Philadelphia Inquirer, 30 July 1967)</ref> He received excellent reviews for his nuanced performance of the multi-faceted Shaw.<ref>(The Philadelphia Enquirer, 1 August 1967)</ref>  The play had a very brief run during the summer of 1967 in [[Denver]], [[Philadelphia]] and [[Falmouth, Massachusetts]].<ref>(News Journal Wilmington Delaware, 9 September 1967</ref><ref>North Adams Transcript Massachusetts, 25 August 1967</ref>\n\nIn early 1968 Boyd was cast as the heavy opposite [[Sean Connery]] and [[Brigitte Bardot]] in the western adventure ''[[Shalako (film)|''Shalako'' (film)]]'', based on the [[Louis L'Amour]] novel.<ref>(Abilene Reporter-News Abilene, Texas Sun, 26 May 1968)</ref> ''Shalako'' was filmed in the early part of 1968 in [[Almer\u00eda]], Spain. After returning to the United States, Boyd took the role of the cruel slave master Nathan MacKay in the Southern \"Slavesploitation\" drama ''[[Slaves (film)|Slaves]]'', also starring [[Ossie Davis]] and songstress [[Dionne Warwick]]. The film was loosely based on the famous [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]] novel ''[[Uncle Tom's Cabin]]''. It was filmed during the summer of 1968 at the supposedly haunted Buena Vista plantation near [[Shreveport]], [[Louisiana]] .<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19680905&id=6qUtAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5J8FAAAAIBAJ&pg=2688,534779&hl=en |title=Film being made about slavery |work=[[Montreal Gazette]] |page=8 |date=5 September 1968 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hauntla.com/buenavista.html|title=The Buena Vista Plantation|website=www.hauntla.com}}</ref> The film was released during the volatile civil rights era and in May 1969 Boyd attended the premiere alongside Dionne Warwick in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2205&dat=19690510&id=CO9fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HwMGAAAAIBAJ&pg=1448,3593309&hl=en |title=Opening Night |newspaper=[[Baltimore Afro-American]] |page=17 |date=10 May 1969 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> Closely following ''[[Slaves (film)|Slaves]]'', Boyd starred in another story about racial tension, this time a World War II made-for-television drama called ''Carter's Army'' (or ''Black Brigade'') which aired in August 1970, featuring a young [[Richard Pryor]].\n\nIt was around this time that Boyd began his interest in [[L. Ron Hubbard]]'s Church of [[Scientology]], which would make him one of the first Hollywood stars to be involved in it.<ref>''Scientology Auditor Magazine'', 1968 article, https://mikemcclaughry.wordpress.com/2016/03/19/blast-from-the-past-ben-hur-actor-stephen-boyd-featured-in-scientology-auditor-mag-1968/</ref>  Boyd had always expressed an interest in esoteric religions.<ref name=Loner>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1356&dat=19660906&id=tMwwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-QUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3955,901669&hl=en \"Stephen Boyd; Loner Who Is Never Alone\"] ''Ocala Star Banner'', 6 September 1966</ref> In an interview in August 1969 with the Detroit Free Press, Boyd explained that Scientology had helped him through the filming of ''Slaves'', and that to him Scientology was \"a process used to make you capable of learning. Scientology is nothing. It means only what you want it to. It is not a church you go to pray, but a church that you go to learn. It is no good unless you apply it. It is the application.\"<ref>''Detroit Free Press'', 1 August 1969, \"Screen Star Stephen Boyd, Since that Chariot Race\"</ref>  Boyd apparently had been elevated to a Scientology Status of OC 6, a position beneath that of [[Clear (Scientology)|Clear]]. Boyd would actually go on to star and narrate a Scientology recruiting film called ''Freedom'' in 1970.<ref>\"Snapping America's Epidemic of Sudden Personality Change\" by Flo Conway, page 145 '...&nbsp;it turned out to be a Scientology meeting. We heard a lecture and saw the introductory film, which was narrated by Stephen Boyd, the film star. It started out in a planetarium and he was standing there as if Scientology had found the stars or something.</ref> A copy of this film can be found at the Library of Congress, but it is not available online via any Scientology resource,<ref>https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/search?searchArg=l+ron+hubbard+film+freedom&searchCode=GKEY^*&searchType=0&recCount=25&sk=en_US</ref> which may indicate a falling out Boyd had with Scientology using his name for recruiting purposes. There is no documentation of his later involvement with Scientology after the early 1970s.\n\n===1970s===\nDuring the 1970s the demand for Boyd in Hollywood diminished, so he focused his attention on European films and several television pilots and shows.<ref>\"Stephen Boyd Likes U.S. Best\" Associated Press, 1 March 1973 Bob Thomas interview with Stephen Boyd</ref> He made three films in Spain with director [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Nieves Conde]], including ''[[Marta (film)|Marta]]'' in 1970, ''[[The Great Swindle (1971 film)|The Great Swindle]]'' in 1971, and ''Casa Manchada'' in 1975. He worked with cult director [[Romain Gary]] in the drug thriller ''[[Kill!]]'' in 1971. He also made several Westerns, including ''[[Hannie Caulder]]'' with Raquel Welch in 1971, ''[[The Man Called Noon]]'' in 1973, ''[[Those Dirty Dogs]]'' in 1973, and ''Potato Fritz'' in 1976. Boyd continued to travel to a wide variety of locations to work, including [[Australia]] for ''[[The Hands of Cormac Joyce]]'' in 1972, [[South Africa]] for ''Control Factor'' and ''The Manipulator'' in 1972-1973, [[Jamaica]] for the scuba diving adventure ''[[The Treasure of Jamaica Reef]]'' in 1972, Florida for the television pilot ''[[Key West]]'' in 1973, and Hawaii in his last acting stint as a guest star on the popular television show ''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]'' in 1977. The episode ''Up the Rebels'' was the premiere episode of ''Hawaii Five-O''&apos;s tenth season, and it aired after Boyd's death on 15 September 1977. His most critically acclaimed role during the 1970s was as a colourful Irish gangster in the UK crime thriller ''[[The Squeeze (1977 film)|The Squeeze]]'' in 1977.\n\nA letter from film producer [[Euan Lloyd]] (who produced such films as ''Shalako'', ''The Man Called Noon'' and ''The Wild Geese''), states that \"Stephen Boyd was one of the nicest, kindest people I have met in my lifetime, rare in this profession.\"<ref>Cushnan, Joe [https://archive.is/20140629144624/http://www.feedaread.com/books/Stephen-Boyd-From-Belfast-To-Hollywood-9781782990864.aspx ''Stephen Boyd: From Belfast To Hollywood''] {{ISBN|9781782990864}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Boyd spent most of his adult life traveling abroad for film work, he made his permanent home in southern [[California]]. At one point in the 1960s, he had three homes there \u2014 one above the Sunset Strip, one in [[Tarzana, Los Angeles|Tarzana]] and another in [[Palm Springs]], where he enjoyed his favorite pastime, golf.<ref name=Loner/> He would make frequent trips back to his hometown of [[Belfast]] in [[Northern Ireland]].<ref>''The Daily Reporter'', Dover, OH, 23 March 1968</ref> to visit his family. On one particular visit to [[Belfast]] in 1971, Boyd exclaimed his dismay about the situation in [[Northern Ireland]] at that time: \"Because of the divisiveness, the potential for displaying to the world all that is good in that lovely land is lost, perhaps even destroyed.\" Boyd was valued so highly by his native city of [[Belfast]] that during his visits he was always given a military escort from the airport to his home for security reasons during [[The Troubles]].<ref name=\"Tower Ticker\">Wiedrich, Bob. ''Chicago Tribune'' \"Tower Ticker\", 5 November 1971</ref>\n\n==Death and commemoration==\nBoyd died unexpectedly of a massive [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] on 2 June 1977 at the age of 45 while playing golf with his wife Elizabeth Mills at the Porter Valley Country Club in [[Northridge, Los Angeles|Northridge, California]]. \"Stephen and Elizabeth were in a golf cart between the fifth and sixth tees when suddenly he said. 'I don't feel well. I don't think we should go on' and slumped over. Elizabeth dragged him out of the cart and gave him artificial respiration, but it was too late.\" <ref>''Detroit Free Press June 9, 1977''.</ref> He was in talks to play the role of the [[Regimental sergeant major|Regimental Sergeant Major]] in [[Euan Lloyd]]'s ''[[The Wild Geese]]'' before his death.<ref name=\"euanlloyd\">Euan Lloyd interview, ''Cinema Retro'' #1</ref>\n\nBoyd was cremated and his ashes were interred in [[Oakwood Memorial Park Cemetery]] in [[Chatsworth, Los Angeles|Chatsworth, California]]. His wife Elizabeth Mills Boyd was interred with him at the time of her death in 2007. Boyd is also remembered on his parents' grave in the Clandeboye Cemetery, Bangor, U.K.<ref name=\"newsletter.co.uk\"/>\n\nOn 4 July 2018, the Ulster History Circle, a voluntary organisation  which erects plaques across the province of Ulster to celebrate people of achievement, commemorated Stephen Boyd with a [[Blue plaque#Northern Ireland|blue plaque]] close to his birthplace <ref>https://goo.gl/maps/6YmUuLxVGwZSBQqq5</ref> at 'Moygara', Shore Road, Whitehouse ([[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]]).<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-44701189\n</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n''Silver Screen'' Magazine in 1960 wrote this about Boyd:\n\n{{quote|A supreme individualist, like most Irishman, he has a wonderful actor's face that easily switches from an engaging smile to sinister menace. Far handsomer in person than on the screen&nbsp;... Stephen Boyd is a lean (180 pounds), well built (six-foot-one) charmer of 31, with a dazzling dimple, light brown curly hair, fair skin and the kind of grey eyes which take on color from what he is wearing. A man of tremendous vitality, a typical Celt, in many roles he veers from humor to anger in the wink of an eye. He dresses conservatively; speaks wittily, and extremely well, though he confesses that he's had almost no formal schooling; is genial and friendly ('I have my brooding hours which wipe that grin off my face').<ref>''Silver Screen'' Magazine, June 1960; \"Stephen Boyd - Sex Appeal + Blarney\" by Maxine Block</ref>}}\n\nJournalist [[Florabel Muir]] described Boyd's appeal in a feature from 1966. \"I would think it has to be his ruggedly masculine good looks. Strong, even craggy features, a wide sympathetic mouth, firm chin, athletic build, wavy dark brown hair, roving 185-lb. frame \u2013 all that plus a musical voice and the savoir faire of a much-traveled fellow \u2013 his films have taken him to many places in the world, and a rolling stone acquires a high polish.\" <ref>Florabel Muir, Valley Morning Star, 18 September 1966</ref>\n\nPersonally, Boyd was popular with Hollywood columnists, including his friend [[Hedda Hopper]], as well as fellow actors and other members of the entertainment industry because of his charm and sense of humor. \"Boyd is the kind of a man who was born to make friends and he has been doing it most of his life...Boyd is a blue-eyed, curly-haired chunk of masculinity, who makes no attempt to hide the fact that he just plain likes people. On the set of ''Ben-Hur'' he rarely occupied the fancy portable dressing room set aside for his use. Instead, he spent his time between scenes sitting around and chatting with electricians, carpenters and his fellow actors. He will discuss any subject and enjoys a good argument. He can, like most Irishmen, sprinkle his talk with wit as well as sagacity.\" <ref>\"The Evening Standard\", Stephen Boyd Prefers Villain Role in ''Ben-Hur'', Pennsylvania, 14 October 1960</ref>\n\nBoyd was first married in 1958 to Italian-born MCA executive Mariella Di Sarzana during the filming of ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]''. They separated after just three weeks. Concerning his short-lived marriage to Sarzana, Boyd would explain, \"It was my fault. I'm an Irish so-and-so when I'm working. I hadn't been married a week when we both knew we had made a mistake. She is a nice girl but we were just not meant for each other. I suppose I wasn't ready for marriage. Maybe I was still too much of an adolescent.\" <ref>''Screen Album'', August\u2013October 1960, page 46.</ref> They officially divorced in early 1959.<ref>''The Free Lance-Star'' 20 December 1958, \"The Divorce Set\"</ref> After his divorce Boyd lived as a bachelor for most of his life, dating several prominent Hollywood starlets throughout the 1960s.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19600428&id=hQswAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_QAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5317,6024126&hl=en \"Stephen Boyd Serious In Romantic Ventures\"] ''Toledo Blade'', 28 April 1960</ref> His secretary Elizabeth Mills was a permanent resident at his Tarzana home during these years, though the two did not marry until 1974.<ref>''Movie Life Jan 1963'', article, \"Let me tell you about Steve Boyd (his very best friend reveals all\" and  The Courier Journal (Louisville Kentucky), 30 December 1962, \"Stephen Boyd is Glad he Escaped Cleopatra with Liz Taylor\" : Excerpt, \"There's an English girl who looks after his house in the Valley here, but marriage does not seem to be on their agenda.\"</ref>\n\nBoyd had a deep and lasting friendship with actress and French icon [[Brigitte Bardot]]. Boyd starred in two movies with Bardot&nbsp;\u2014 ''[[The Night Heaven Fell]]'' in 1958 and ''[[Shalako (film)|Shalako]]'' in 1968. During the filming of ''[[Shalako]]'' in Almeria, Spain, Bardot and Boyd's close relationship and open affection for each other sparked numerous rumors of a possible affair.<ref name=\"Photoplay Film 1968\">''Photoplay Film'', September 1968, \"Boyd and Bardot- the Truth Behind Those Rumors\"</ref> It even caused Brigitte's husband at the time, [[Gunter Sachs]], to ask for a divorce.<ref>''The Milwaukee Journal'', 8 March 1968</ref> In Bardot's autobiography, she described the events and states that Boyd \"was never her lover, but a tender and attentive friend.\"<ref>\"Stephen n'ayant jamais \u00e9t\u00e9 mon amant, mais uniquement un ami tendre et attentionn\u00e9!\" Bardot, Brigitte. ''Initials B.B.'', 1995</ref> In an interview with ''Photoplay Film'' in 1968, Boyd said, \"Bardot is always Bardot. She's marvelous. She's an enormous star and she's a unique, marvelous woman. I adore her.\" <ref name=\"Photoplay Film 1968\"/> Even though both actors denied the affair, the press was \"convinced there was a romance afoot, that Brigitte and Boyd openly displayed their affection for each other, but that publication of the report on their romance cooled it.\" <ref>\"Boyd on Bardot\", Photolay Film Monthly, September 1968, Raymond Palmer Interviews Stephen Boyd</ref>\n\n[[File:Dolores Hart en Stephen Boyd (1961).jpg|thumb|Hart and Boyd in 1961]]\nBoyd also had a close relationship with actress [[Dolores Hart]]. Hart describes what was her only romance with a co-star in her autobiography ''The Ear of the Heart''.<ref>Hart, Dolores. ''The Ear of the Heart'', 2013</ref> Boyd eventually rejected her advances, but they remained close friends even after she turned to the cloistered life of a nun in 1963. He visited her in 1966 at the Abbey of Regina Laudis in Connecticut and remained in communication with her until the early 1970s.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1368&dat=19660207&id=N3ZQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rRAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4614,1215354&hl=en \"Stephen Boyd to Visit Dolores Hart, now Nun\"] ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', 7 February 1966</ref>\n\nStephen Boyd's most passionate affair seems to have been with beautiful Austrian actress [[Marisa Mell]].<ref>http://marisa-mell.blogspot.com/2008/09/marta-or-dopo-di-che-uccide-il-maschio.htm</ref> They met while filming the movie ''[[Marta (film)|Marta]]'' in 1970. Boyd initially dodged Marisa Mell's amorous advances, but during the second film they made together, ''[[The Great Swindle (1971 film)|The Great Swindle]]'', the two became inseparable lovers.<ref name=\"Mell, Marisa. Coverlove, 1990\">Mell, Marisa. ''Coverlove'', 1990</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceC\">Schneider, Andre. ''Die Feuerblume: \u00dcber Marisa Mell und ihre Filme'', 2013</ref> They married in a gypsy camp on the outskirts of  [[Madrid]] in late 1971. The ceremony included a wrist cutting exchange of blood to seal their bond.<ref>''The Record Argus'', 26 October 1971, \"Boyd's Bride will be Blood Brother\"</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> The marriage was not considered legal, but Marisa Mell said, \"Who cares? In our minds it will be real.\"<ref>''The San Bernardino County Sun'', 10 November 1971</ref> According to Marisa Mell, their affair was so intense that while living in Rome they made a trip to the Italian town of Sarsina for a ritual exorcism at the Cathedral of St. Vicinius.<ref name=\"Mell, Marisa. Coverlove, 1990\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> Boyd abruptly broke off the affair after the intensity apparently became too much to bear.<ref name=\"Mell, Marisa. Coverlove, 1990\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> In early 1972, after Boyd's departure, Mell had this to say about the break-up of their relationship: \"We both believe in reincarnation, and we realized we've already been lovers in three different lifetimes, and in each one I made him suffer terribly.\"<ref>''The Akron Beacon Journal, June 16, 1972''</ref> For her part, Mell would fondly remember Boyd many years later in her autobiography 'Cover Love' from 1990, dedicating a whole chapter to their affair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marisa-mell.blogspot.com/search/label/Stephen%2BBoyd.|title=MARISA MELL|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nBoyd's last marriage took place in 1974 to Elizabeth Mills,<ref>''Detroit Free Press June 9, 1977 'Just a few of the late Stephen Boyd's closest friends knew that three years ago in London he married Elizabeth Mills, whom he had been going with for many years''</ref> a secretary at the British Arts Council, whom he had known since 1953. Elizabeth Mills followed Boyd to the United States in the late 1950s and was his personal assistant, friend and confidante for many years before marrying him in the mid-1970s.<ref>[http://www.allaboutstephenboyd.com/biography.htm Stephen Boyd infosite]; accessed 28 June 2014.</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Black 13]]'' (1953) as Policeman (uncredited)\n* ''[[Lilacs in the Spring]]'' (1954) as Beaumont's Poolside Companion (uncredited)\n* ''[[An Alligator Named Daisy]]'' (1955) as Albert O'Shannon\n* ''Born for Trouble'' (1955)\n* ''[[The Man Who Never Was]]'' (1956) as Patrick O'Reilly\n* ''[[A Hill in Korea]]'' (1956) as Pvt. Sims\n* ''[[Seven Waves Away]]'' (1957) as Will McKinley\n* ''[[Island in the Sun (film)|Island in the Sun]]'' (1957) as Euan Templeton\n* ''[[Seven Thunders (film)|Seven Thunders]]'' (1957) as Dave\n* ''[[The Night Heaven Fell|Les bijoutiers du clair de lune]]'' (1958) as Lambert\n* ''[[The Bravados]]'' (1958) as Bill Zachary\n* ''[[Woman Obsessed]]'' (1959) as Fred Carter\n* ''[[The Best of Everything (film)|The Best of Everything]]'' (1959) as Mike Rice\n* ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]'' (1959) as [[Messala (Ben-Hur)|Messala]]\n* ''[[The Big Gamble (1961 film)|The Big Gamble]]'' (1961) as Vic Brennan\n* ''[[Lisa (1962 film)|Lisa]]'' (1962) as Peter Jongman\n* ''[[Billy Rose's Jumbo|Jumbo]]'' (1962) as Sam Rawlins\n* ''[[Imperial Venus (film)|Imperial Venus]]'' (1962) as Jules de Canouville\n* ''[[The Third Secret (film)|The Third Secret]]'' (1964) as Alex Stedman\n* ''[[The Fall of the Roman Empire (film)|The Fall of the Roman Empire]]'' (1964) as Livius\n* ''[[Genghis Khan (1965 film)|Genghis Khan]]'' (1965) as Jamuga\n* ''[[The Oscar (film)|The Oscar]]'' (1966) as Frank Fane\n* ''[[The Poppy Is Also a Flower]]'' (1966) as Benson\n* ''[[Fantastic Voyage]]'' (1966) as Grant\n* ''[[The Bible: In the Beginning...]]'' (1966) as [[Nimrod]]\n* ''[[The Caper of the Golden Bulls]]'' (1967) as Peter Churchman\n* ''[[Assignment K]]'' (1968) as Philip Scott\n* ''[[Shalako (film)|Shalako]]'' (1968) as Bosky Fulton\n* ''[[Slaves (film)|Slaves]]'' (1969) as MacKay\n* ''[[Carter's Army]]'' (1970, TV Movie) as Capt. Beau Carter\n* ''Historia de una traici\u00f3n'' (1971) as Arturo\n* ''[[Marta (film)|Marta]]'' (1971) as Don Miguel\n* ''African Story'' (1971) as Arnold Tiller\n* ''[[Hannie Caulder]]'' (1971) as The Preacher (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Great Swindle (1971 film)|The Great Swindle]]'' (1971) as Dave Barton\n* ''[[Kill! Kill! Kill! Kill!]]'' (1971) as Brad Killian\n* ''[[The Devil Has Seven Faces]]'' (1972) as Le\u00f3n Urrut\u00eda, joyero\n* ''[[The Hands of Cormac Joyce]]'' (1972, TV Movie) as Cormac Joyce\n* ''[[Those Dirty Dogs]]'' (1973) as Cpt. Chadwood Willer\n* ''[[The Big Game (1972 film)|The Big Game]]'' (1973) as Leyton van Dyk\n* ''[[The Man Called Noon]]'' (1973) as Rimes\n* ''[[The Treasure of Jamaica Reef]]'' (1974) as Hugo Graham\n* ''[[The Left Hand of the Law]]'' (1975) as Lanza\n* ''L'uomo che sfid\u00f2 l'organizzazione'' (1975) as Inspector Stephen McCormick\n* ''Potato Fritz'' (1976) as Bill Ardisson\n* ''[[Lady Dracula]]'' (1977) as [[Count Dracula]]\n* ''[[The Squeeze (1977 film)|The Squeeze]]'' (1977) as Vic\n* ''[[Women in Hospital]]'' (1977) as Dr. Oberhoff\n* ''Impossible Love'' (1977) as Alvaro\n* ''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]'' (1977, TV Series) as Daniel Costigan (final appearance)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{IMDb name|0000963}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=20469|name=Stephen Boyd}}\n* {{findagrave|1629}}\n* http://leglatin.pagesperso-orange.fr/boyd/\n* https://stephenboydblog.wordpress.com\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-12135044 \"Stephen Boyd: The Busker Who Became a Screen Idol\"] BBC News; retrieved 23 July 2011\n* [http://www.literarybelfast.org/article/3794/the-man-who-never-was- \"The Man Who Never Was?\"] Literary Belfast; retrieved 23 July 2011\n{{Golden Globe Award Best Supporting Actor Motion Picture}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boyd, Stephen}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actor Golden Globe (film) winners]]\n[[Category:Male film actors from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Burials at Oakwood Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n[[Category:People from Ballyclare]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ballyclare High School]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox contract players]]\n[[Category:20th-century male actors from Northern Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Stephen Boyd\n| image        = Stephen Boyd.jpg\n| caption      = Boyd in 1961\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1931|07|04|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Glengormley]], [[County Antrim]], Northern Ireland\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1977|06|02|1931|07|04|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Northridge, Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n| birth_name   = William Millar\n| years_active = 1950\u20131977\n| occupation   = Actor\n| resting_place = [[Oakwood Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n| partner   = [[Marisa Mell]] (1970-1972)\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Mariella di Sarzana<br>|1958|1959|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Elizabeth Mills<br>| 1974|1977|end=his death}}\n}}\n\n'''Stephen Boyd''' (4 July 1931&nbsp;\u2013 2 June 1977) was a [[Northern Irish]] actor. A native of [[Glengormley]], [[County Antrim]],<ref name=bbc>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-12135044 \"Stephen Boyd: The Busker Who Became a Screen Idol\"] BBC News; retrieved 14 April 2014.</ref> Boyd appeared in some 60 films, most notably as the villainous Messala in ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]'' (1959), a role that earned him the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]]. He received his second  [[Golden Globe Award]] nomination for ''[[Billy Rose's Jumbo]]'' (1962). He also appeared, sometimes as a hero and sometimes as a malefactor, in the major big-screen productions ''[[The Night Heaven Fell|Les bijoutiers du clair de lune]]'' (1958), ''[[The Bravados]]'' (1958), ''[[Imperial Venus (film)|Imperial Venus]]'' (1962), ''[[The Fall of the Roman Empire (film)|The Fall of the Roman Empire]]'' (1964), ''[[Genghis Khan (1965 film)|Genghis Khan]]'' (1965), ''[[Fantastic Voyage]]'' (1966) and ''[[Shalako (film)|Shalako]]'' (1968).\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\nStephen Boyd \u2013 real name William Millar \u2013 was born in a house, long since demolished, at the corner of the Doagh Road, Whitehouse on 4 July 1931.<ref>[http://daggy.name/cop/bkofdead/99999989.htm Profile], daggy.name/cop/bkofdead; accessed 28 June 2014.</ref> Boyd was the youngest of nine siblings born to Irish/Canadian parents, James Alexander Millar and his wife Martha Boyd. At a very early age, William, or Billy as he was known, moved with the family to live in Glengormley. Boyd attended the local Public Elementary School and [[Ballyclare High School]], but at the age of fourteen Boyd quit school to take up other jobs to help support his family. He eventually joined the Ulster Group Theatre where he learned the behind the scenes tasks of the theatre. He became well known in Belfast for his contributions as a gravel-voiced policeman on the Ulster Radio program \"The McCooeys\", the story of a Belfast family written by Joseph Tomelty.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''The Journal News - White Plains New York, 09 Jul 1969''</ref><ref name=\"newsletter.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/blue-plaque-honour-for-ulster-born-hollywood-star-stephen-boyd-1-8552887|title=Blue plaque honour for Ulster-born Hollywood star Stephen Boyd|publisher=}}</ref> Boyd eventually worked his way up to character parts and then starring roles. By nineteen he had toured Canada with summer stock companies. In 1950 he made a coast to coast tour of America with the [[Clare Tree Major]] Company,<ref>''Stephen Boyd, The Man Who Never Wants to Pour Another Coffee, by John Neal''</ref> 1956 performing ''[[A Streetcar Named Desire]]'' <ref>''Daily News, NY, NY May 5, 1963''</ref> in the lead role as [[Stanley Kowalski]]. Boyd would later recall this as \"the best performance I ever gave in my life\". <ref>''Movieland Magazine interview December of 1962''</ref>\n\nBy the time he was twenty, Boyd had a wide range of theatre experience, but he longed for the big stage.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">''Movie Screen'' Stephen Boyd Interview, June 1960</ref> In 1952 Boyd moved to London and worked in a cafeteria and busked outside a cinema in Leicester Square to get money as he was literally close to starvation.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Boyd caught his first break as a doorman at the Odeon Theatre. The Leicester Square Cinema across the street recruited him to usher attendees during the British Academy Awards in the early 1950s. During the awards ceremony he was noticed by actor Sir [[Michael Redgrave]], who used his connections to introduce Boyd to the director of the Windsor Repertory Group.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> At this point Boyd's stage career in the U.K. began to flourish with performances in \"The Deep Blue Sea\" and \"Barnett's Folly\" <ref>''Movieland'' Magazine, December 1962</ref>\n\n===Early roles===\nBoyd's first role which brought him acclaim<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2194&dat=19560405&id=X7cxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dOQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=7080,904122&hl=en |title=Irish-Canadian Film Actor Gains Stardom in Big Part |newspaper=Ottawa Citizen |page=28 |date=5 April 1956 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> was as an Irish spy in the movie ''[[The Man Who Never Was]]'', based on the book by [[Ewen Montagu]]. The movie was released in April 1956.\n\nShortly thereafter he signed a ten-year contract with [[20th Century Fox]] studios,<ref>''Hedda Hopper, Los Angeles Times, May 29, 1956''</ref> who began prepping him for Hollywood. But it would be a while until Boyd actually set foot on a Hollywood back-lot. Boyd's next stop was Portugal to make ''[[A Hill in Korea]]'', which also featured future stars [[Michael Caine]] and [[Robert Shaw (British actor)|Robert Shaw]].<ref>Michael Caine, ''What's it all About?'', page 114-115</ref> In June 1956, Boyd was cast in the nautical, ship-wreck adventure ''[[Seven Waves Away|Abandon Ship!]]'' for Columbia Studios starring [[Tyrone Power]]. This was filmed in the summer of 1956 in London where the British Navy  built a huge 35,000 gallon water tank for the movie.<ref>''St. Louis Dispatch'' 14 July 1956</ref>\n\nIn November 1956, for Twentieth Century Fox, Boyd traveled to the [[British West Indies]] as part of a large ensemble cast in [[Darryl Zanuck]]'s racially provocative film ''[[Island in the Sun (film)|Island in the Sun]] starring [[Dorothy Dandridge]]'', based on the [[Alec Waugh]] novel.<ref>''The Corpus Christi Caller, Nov 27, 1956''</ref> Boyd portrayed a young English aristocrat who becomes the lover of [[Joan Collins]]. Boyd would be loaned out to the [[J. Arthur Rank]] production of ''[[Seven Thunders (film)|Seven Thunders]] (Beast of Marseilles)'', a [[World War II]] romance set in Nazi-occupied Marseilles.<ref>''The Los Angeles Times, March 23, 1957''</ref> This movie was filmed on location in [[Marseilles]] and at [[Pinewood Studios]] in London in the spring of 1957 <ref>''https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0050174/locations?ref_=tt_dt_dt''</ref>  and featured Boyd in his most prominent starring film role yet.\n\nAround the same time French actress [[Brigitte Bardot]] was given the opportunity to cast her own leading man in her next movie after her success in [[Roger Vadim]]'s ''[[And God Created Woman (1956 film)|And God Created Woman]]'', and she chose Boyd.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1301&dat=19580504&id=g3dWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8eQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3095,1129485&hl=en |last=Lambert |first=John |title=Bardot Picks a Co-Star |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=4 May 1958 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> From August to October 1957,<ref>''Philadelphia Inquirer August 29, 1957''</ref> Bardot, Boyd and [[Alida Valli]] filmed the lusty romance ''[[The Night Heaven Fell]]'', directed by [[Roger Vadim]] in Paris and in the region of [[M\u00e1laga]], [[Spain]], specifically the small, white-washed town of Mijas.<ref>''Ottawa Citizen Feb 15, 1958''</ref> Being in the Bardot spotlight added much to Boyd's film credit, in addition to bringing him notice in Hollywood.<ref>The Salt Lake Tribune, 24 June 1958,  ''Ireland's Boyd- A Man Apart&nbsp;\u2014 And all Because of Bardot''</ref>\n\nStephen Boyd finally arrived in Hollywood in January 1958 to take on his first true Hollywood role as the leader of a quartet of renegade outlaws in the Twentieth Century Fox western ''[[The Bravados]]'', which starred [[Gregory Peck]] and [[Joan Collins]]. Even though this was a Hollywood production, the actual filming took place in [[Morelia]], Mexico.<ref>''Lee Belser, Lubbock Evening Journal, February 28, 1958''</ref>\n\n===''Ben-Hur''===\nAfter the filming of ''[[The Bravados]]'' was complete in late March 1958, Stephen Boyd returned to Hollywood to audition for the coveted role of Messala in [[MGM]]'s upcoming epic ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]''. Many other actors, including [[Victor Mature]], [[Kirk Douglas]], [[Leslie Nielsen]] and [[Stewart Granger]] had been considered for the part,<ref>''The Los Angeles Times, April 17, 1958''</ref> but Stephen Boyd's screen test convinced director [[William Wyler]] that he had found the perfect villain for his epic, as Wyler had also admired Boyd's performance in ''[[The Man Who Never Was]]'' the previous year. Boyd was hurried off to join actor [[Charlton Heston]] in Rome in May 1958 to learn the chariot racing aspect of his role. Heston had already been practicing behind the chariot for weeks, so Boyd needed to learn quickly. Boyd was also required to wear brown contact lenses as Messala, which irritated his eyes and caused vision problems for a few months after the movie was completed. Despite this, Boyd described the filming experience of ''Ben-Hur'' (which took place in [[Cinecitt\u00e0]] Studios in Rome), as the most exciting experience of his life.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19581204&id=zjkxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5wAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7405,6177173&hl=en |title=Stephen Boyd Endures Agony for Art's Sake |last=Heffernan |first=Harold |newspaper=Toledo Blade |date=4 December 1958 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nYears after the movie was released, interim ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]'' screenwriter and novelist [[Gore Vidal]] revealed that Boyd had portrayed his famous character [[Messala (Ben-Hur)|Messala]] in ''Ben-Hur'' with an underlying homosexual energy, as instructed to by [[Gore Vidal]] when he greets Ben-Hur [[Charlton Heston]] in the opening sequence. In Gore Vidal's autobiography \"Palimpsest,\"<ref name=\"Gore Vidal pages 303\">''Palimpsest by Gore Vidal, pages 303 to 307, published in 1996''</ref> Vidal describes his discussion first with director [[William Wyler]], concerning Messala's underlying motivation, namely that Messala and Judah Ben-Hur had previously been lovers.  This was based on an idea by Vidal to enhance the tension between the two main antagonists. Wyler specifically told Vidal, \"You talk to Boyd. But don't ''you'' say a word to Chuck or he'll fall apart.\" <ref>(Palimpsest, by Gore Vidal, Page 306)</ref> In \"Palimpsest\", Vidal said, \"Over the next few years, whenever we met (William Wyler), we quarreled amiably over what I had put in the scene and what Steven Boyd is clearly playing.\"  Vidal would later come into conflict with actor [[Charlton Heston]] about his version of the Messala/Ben-Hur relationship and the implications surrounding [[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]].<ref name=\"Gore Vidal pages 303\"/>\n\nAfter the filming of ''Ben-Hur'' was completed Boyd returned to Hollywood in early 1959 to star with [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] winner [[Susan Hayward]] in the Canadian-based drama ''[[Woman Obsessed]]''. Some advertisements for this movie labeled Boyd as \"The New Gable.\"<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19580812&id=TAUkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4QAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7250,1107861&hl=en ''Toledo Blade''] 12 August 1958</ref>  He was then part of another excellent ensemble cast in the adaptation of [[Rona Jaffe]]'s novel ''[[The Best of Everything (film)|The Best of Everything]]'', filmed in May and June 1959 at Fox Studios in Hollywood and on location in New York City.\n\n[[File:Stephen Boyd in Ben Hur trailer.jpg|thumb|From the trailer for the film ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]'' (1959).]]\n\n''Ben-Hur'' was released in December 1959 and immediately made Boyd an international star. His portrayal of the Roman tribune Messala brought in rave reviews. Press columnist Erskine Johnson wrote, \"A brass hat and the armor of a Roman warrior in ''Ben-Hur'' does for Stephen Boyd what a tight dress does for Marilyn Monroe.\"<ref>''The Odessa American'', 19 December 1959, \"Actor Stephen Boyd Really Packs Wallop\"</ref> Ruth Waterbury, in her Boyd feature in the Pittsburgh Post Gazette, would describe Boyd's character as \"the dangerously masculine and quite magnificent Messala.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1129&dat=19610715&id=P8daAAAAIBAJ&sjid=NmwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4358,3443168&hl=en |title=Boydie |last=Waterbury |first=Ruth |newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |date=15 July 1961 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> ''Modern Screen'' magazine in 1960 stated that Boyd's  ruthless Messala had \"lost the chariot race but captured the sympathy and sex appeal of ''Ben-Hur''.\"<ref>''Modern Screen'', Stephen Boyd \"Introducing the Sensational Star of Ben Hur and Best of Everything\", October\u2013December 1960</ref>\n\n===1960s===\nBoyd was featured in the popular TV program ''[[This Is Your Life]]'' on 3 February 1960, which featured many of Boyd's family members and acquaintances (including Michael Redgrave) telling stories about his early life and film career. This should be some indication of how \"Stephen Boyd fever\" was catching. Newspaper columnists were getting swarmed with letters from female fans of all ages wanting to know more about Boyd.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19600309&id=sQcvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bE4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=7562,2549137&hl=en \"Maids, Matrons Here Cheering For Stephen Boyd\"] ''Pittsburgh Press'' 9 March 1960</ref> He was being sent dozens of starring roles, most of which he had to turn down due to other obligations. He opted out of the biblical epic ''[[The Story of Ruth]]'', which didn't please Fox studios, and he was one of the front-runners to star with [[Marilyn Monroe]] in her picture ''Let's Make Love''.<ref>''The News Review'' 24 March 1960, \"Oscar Ground Rules Hazy For Supporting Actor Roles\"</ref>\n\nIn early 1960 Boyd won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]] for his performance in ''Ben-Hur''.<ref name=\"IMDb profile\">[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000963/bio IMDb profile], imdb.com; accessed 28 June 2014.</ref> In January 1960 Boyd made a guest appearance alongside the silent-era ''Ben-Hur'' stars [[Ramon Novarro]] and [[Francis X. Bushman]] on [[Hedda Hopper]]'s special television programme ''Hedda Hopper's Hollywood''.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1356&dat=19600108&id=Q3hhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3wQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6554,1304721&hl=en \"Hedda Hopper's Show on Sunday\"] ''Ocala Star Banner'', 8 January 1960</ref> In February 1960 he starred in the [[Playhouse 90]] television performance called ''The Sound of Trumpets'' with [[Dolores Hart]], which garnered good reviews. He also appeared as a singing guest on [[The Dinah Shore Chevy Show]] on 13 March 1960 where he performed two Irish folk songs with Dinah Shore, \"The Leprechaun Song\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.traditionalmusic.co.uk/irish-songs-ballads-lyrics/leprechaun_song.htm|title=Irish Music, Song and Ballad Lyrics for: Leprechaun Song|website=www.traditionalmusic.co.uk}}</ref> and \"Molly Malone\", and an Irish step dance.<ref>(Arizona Republic, 13 March 1960)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x5d2sdr_dinah-shore-03-13-1960-stephen-boyd-shelley-berman_tv|title=Dinah Shore (03_13_1960) - STEPHEN BOYD, SHELLEY BERMAN - Video Dailymotion|date=24 February 2017|website=Dailymotion}}</ref>\n\nBoyd himself chose to do roles which he felt comfortable in. His next choice was ''[[The Big Gamble (1961 film)|The Big Gamble]]'', which featured [[Darryl F. Zanuck]]'s current paramour and French icon [[Juliette Gr\u00e9co]]. It was filmed on the [[Ivory Coast]] of [[West Africa]], [[Dublin]] and the southern part of France in the spring and summer of 1961. The adventure of making this film almost outdid the adventure in the film itself<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1356&dat=19600801&id=YvkjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4QQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1488,3307578&hl=en |title=Trout Fly With Sequins- That's French Fishing Flair |work=Ocala Star-Banner |page=5 |date=1 August 1960 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=861&dat=19601002&id=sOhHAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LoAMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3018,3351049&hl=en |title=Africa's Most Rabid Film Fans |last=Bacon |first=James |work=[[The Victoria Advocate]] |agency=Associated Press |location=London |page=11 |date=2 October 1960 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> as the crew slept in tents in the jungle that were guarded by natives on parole for cannibalism.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1873&dat=19600925&id=iokeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rswEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2690,3861205&hl=en |title=She Slept with the Cannibals |newspaper=Daytona Beach Morning Journal |page=5C |date=25 September 1960 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>  Boyd nearly drowned in the Ard\u00e8che river during the making of the film. Luckily he was saved by his co-star and excellent swimmer [[David Wayne]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1368&dat=19600705&id=Zl4xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=eg8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2640,2510221&hl=en |title=Wayne Saves Drowning Actor |newspaper=Milwaukee Sentinel |date=5 July 1960 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> Boyd spoke about this incident during his appearance on the popular TV programme ''[[What's My Line?]]'' which aired on 11 December 1960.\n\nBoyd was originally chosen to play [[Mark Antony]] opposite [[Elizabeth Taylor]] in 20th Century Fox's epic production of ''[[Cleopatra (1963 film)|Cleopatra]]'' ([[1963 in film|1963]]) under the direction of [[Rouben Mamoulian]]. He began film work in September 1960 but eventually withdrew from the problem-plagued production after Elizabeth Taylor's severe illness postponed the film for months. (''Cleopatra'' was later directed by [[Joseph L. Mankiewicz]], and the role of Mark Antony went to [[Richard Burton]].)<ref name=\"imdb\">{{IMDb name|0000963}}</ref> During this period of waiting in April 1961 Stephen Boyd was sent to [[Cairo]], Egypt on a publicity tour by [[Twentieth Century Fox]] along with fellow actors [[Julie Newmar]] and [[Barbara Eden]] to attend the inaugural ceremony of the sound and light show at the pyramids of [[Giza]].<ref>''The Los Angeles Times,  13 Apr 1961, Thu,  Page 86''</ref><ref>''Chicago Daily Tribune May 11, 1961''</ref>\n\nAfter several months without active work, Boyd was thrilled to finally get his first post-Cleopatra role.<ref>(The Bridgeport Post, 11 July 1961, \"Stephen Boyd Ends Big Wait\")</ref> The film was ''[[The Inspector (1962 film)|The Inspector]]'', renamed ''Lisa'' for the American release. It was based on the novel by [[Jan de Hartog]] and co- starred actress [[Dolores Hart]]. The film was made in [[Amsterdam]], London and Wales during the summer of 1961. On 9 January 1962, Boyd was featured in a television film from [[General Electric Theater]] called ''The Wall Between'', co-starring [[Ronald Reagan]] and [[Gloria Talbott]].<ref>''The Daily Herald, Provo Utah, 08 January 1962''</ref>  Next, Boyd was again loaned out to MGM Studios to star with [[Doris Day]] in the circus musical ''[[Billy Rose's Jumbo]]'', filmed during the early part of 1962; the role earned Boyd a nomination for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]].\n\nBoyd flew to Rome in the summer of 1962 to act with Italian superstar [[Gina Lollobrigida]] in her long-time pet project ''[[Imperial Venus (film)|Imperial Venus]]'', a romantic epic about the many loves of [[Pauline Bonaparte]], the sister of [[Napoleon]]. This film was the first film to be banned by the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] for male nudity. Boyd appeared in a humorous bedroom scene, naked with only his lower half covered by a bed-sheet.<ref>''Ottawa Citizen'', 10 July 1964, [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2194&dat=19640710&id=Gr0yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Fe0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=1232,2402566&hl=en \"Nude Movie Scenes\u2026How about Lassie?\"]</ref> The suggestion of nudity was too much for the censors and the movie was never released in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19841204&id=qNUvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=CKYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6488,4632441&hl=en |title=Names Etcetera |newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]] |agency=Knight-Ridder |page=30 |date=4 December 1984 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>  Boyd returned to the States briefly after finishing [[Imperial Venus]] where he appeared for the second time on [[The Dinah Shore Chevy Show]], which aired on 11 November 1962. For thus program Boyd was a last minute replacement for actor [[James Garner]] and joined Shore and entertainer [[Dean Martin]] for a few musical numbers.<ref>''Argus Leader (Sioux Falls, South Dakota), November 10, 1962''</ref><ref>''The Times Herald (Port Huron, Michigan), November 10, 1962.''</ref>\n\nBoyd arrived in Spain in early 1963 to begin work on [[Samuel Bronston]]'s massive production of the''[[The Fall of the Roman Empire (film)|The Fall of the Roman Empire]]'', directed by [[Anthony Mann]]. This was filmed during a severely cold winter in Europe and the production in the [[Sierra de Guadarrama]] of Spain encountered several challenges with the snow.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1755&dat=19630205&id=p7gqAAAAIBAJ&sjid=pGUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7159,1061883&hl=en |title=Some Portuguese See Their First Snow |agency=Associated Press |location=London |newspaper=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]] |page=10 |date=5 February 1963 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref><ref>''\"Rome in Madrid\" (1964 Making of The Fall of the Roman Empire film), https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GnWkzdajxwQ''</ref> Boyd's co-star was another Italian legend, Sophia Loren. Boyd also had the opportunity to ride another chariot in this film. Although the movie did well internationally when it was released in April 1964, it was a box office failure in the United States and signaled the end of Roman epics in the 1960s. More appreciated with the passing of time, ''[[The Fall of the Roman Empire (film)|The Fall of the Roman Empire]]'' was also recognized by critics as being a major inspiration for Ridley Scott's [[Academy Award]] winning movie ''[[Gladiator (2000 film)|Gladiator]].''\n<ref>The Fall of the Roman Empire  Film And History by Martin M Winkler, 2009</ref>\n\nBoyd flew back to Hollywood in the summer to star in a [[Bob Hope Presents the Chrysler Theatre]] TV Program with [[Louis Jourdan]] called ''War of Nerves'', which aired on 3 January 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Fjq2oXMBTpc|title=The Chrysler Theater: \"War of Nerves\" (1964)|first=|last=GR160289|date=10 July 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> He then returned to Europe to film the suspenseful ''[[The Third Secret (film)]]'' starring  [[Pamela Franklin]] and [[Diane Cilento]].\n\nOn 23 December 1963, Stephen Boyd became a naturalized U.S. citizen during a ceremony at the Federal Building in Los Angeles, California.<ref>Los Angeles Times, 25 December 1963</ref>\n\nStephen Boyd was originally cast as the lead in Anthony Mann's WWII drama \"''The Unknown Battle''\", which was set to film in early 1964 with co-stars [[Elke Sommer]] and [[Anthony Perkins]] in Norway.<ref>The Los Angeles Times, 24 Jan 1964</ref><ref>The Progress Index, 24 Feb 1964</ref> After several weeks of waiting, studio funding for the project fell though.<ref>Asbury Park Press, 2 July 1964</ref> Boyd sued Mann for $500,000 for a breach of contract, missed time and other lost film opportunities.<ref>Philadelphia Inquirer, 25 April 1964</ref> The project was finally completed by Mann a year later and released as ''[[Heroes of Telemark]]'' with [[Kirk Douglas]] replacing Boyd as the lead.<ref>Looking at Hollywood: Steve Boyd Is Back After Stint Abroad Hopper, Hedda. Chicago Tribune (1963\u2013Current file) [Chicago, Ill] 29 December 1964: b11.</ref>\n\nIn 1964 Boyd continued to make films in Europe, traveling to [[Yugoslavia]] to star as the villain Jamuga in the epic ''[[Genghis Khan (1965 film)|Genghis Khan]]''. Boyd was the top billed and therefore the top paid star in the epic, and this apparently caused friction with up-and-coming star [[Omar Sharif]].<ref>''Miami News'' 25 June 1965, \"More Dramatics than Spectacle in Genghis Khan\"</ref> After completing ''Genghis Khan'', Boyd trekked to [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]] for a brief appearance as the regal King [[Nimrod]] at [[The Tower of Babel]] in [[Dino de Laurentiis]]'s production of ''[[The Bible: In the Beginning...|The Bible]]'', directed by [[John Huston]].<ref>''Chicago Tribune'', 29 December 1964, \"Steve Boyd Is Back After Stint Abroad\"</ref>\n\nAfter all this globe-trotting, the world weary Boyd was very happy to return to the United States to start work on the Twentieth Century Fox science fiction adventure ''[[Fantastic Voyage]]'', co-starring with soon-to-be icon [[Raquel Welch]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1774&dat=19650318&id=3uQhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=oWUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2656,4646021&hl=en |title=Movie Actor Seeks Hollywood Home |agency=UPI |location=Hollywood |work=Sarasota Herald-Tribune |date=18 March 1965 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>  This was filmed in the early part of 1965. In the summer of 1965, Boyd joined German star [[Elke Sommer]] and music legend [[Tony Bennett]] to film the Hollywood drama ''[[The Oscar (film)|The Oscar]]'', based on the eponymous [[Richard Sale (director)|Richard Sale]] novel. The movie was a popular success, but maligned by film critics.<ref>''The Daily Times News'', Burlington North Carolina, 1 August 1966, \"Movie Argument Continues\"</ref> Boyd would make a 10-day visit to [[Iran]] in December 1965 to film his scenes for the [[United Nations]] film project ''[[The Poppy Is Also a Flower]]'',<ref>(Hedda Hopper, Chicago Tribune, 31 December 1965</ref> written by [[James Bond]] creator [[Ian Fleming]].\n\nIn 1966 the producer of ''[[The Oscar (film)|The Oscar]]'', [[Joseph E. Levine|Joseph Levine]], hired Boyd for his next film project, ''[[The Caper of the Golden Bulls]]'', based on a [[William McGivern]] novel. This movie was partly filmed on location in Spain in the summer of 1966. The actors, including Boyd, took part in the famous Feria del Toro de San Fermin festival in [[Pamplona]] (known as the Running of the Bulls).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19660711&id=4TQgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=I1AEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6420,3584537&hl=en |title=Sheilah Graham |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Press]] |page=23 |date=11 July 1966 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nTwo of Boyd's projects were ranked among the top twenty-five grossing films of 1966; ''[[The Bible: In the Beginning...|The Bible]]'' at number one and  ''[[Fantastic Voyage]]'' at twenty.\n\nNext, Boyd starred in a spy thriller ''[[Assignment K]]'' with Swedish model/actress [[Camilla Sparv]], which was filmed in Germany, Austria and London during February and March 1967.<ref>(The Los Angeles Times, 10 January 1967)</ref> Boyd grew a full beard <ref>(Arizona Republic 12 June 1967)</ref> for his next role as the iconic Irish playwright and critic [[George Bernard Shaw]] in the [[Off-Broadway]] play called ''The Bashful Genius'' written by Harold Callen. This was Boyd's first return to the stage since the mid-1950s, and the experience for Boyd was immensely rewarding on a personal level.<ref>(The Philadelphia Inquirer, 30 July 1967)</ref> He received excellent reviews for his nuanced performance of the multi-faceted Shaw.<ref>(The Philadelphia Enquirer, 1 August 1967)</ref>  The play had a very brief run during the summer of 1967 in [[Denver]], [[Philadelphia]] and [[Falmouth, Massachusetts]].<ref>(News Journal Wilmington Delaware, 9 September 1967</ref><ref>North Adams Transcript Massachusetts, 25 August 1967</ref>\n\nIn early 1968 Boyd was cast as the heavy opposite [[Sean Connery]] and [[Brigitte Bardot]] in the western adventure ''[[Shalako (film)|''Shalako'' (film)]]'', based on the [[Louis L'Amour]] novel.<ref>(Abilene Reporter-News Abilene, Texas Sun, 26 May 1968)</ref> ''Shalako'' was filmed in the early part of 1968 in [[Almer\u00eda]], Spain. After returning to the United States, Boyd took the role of the cruel slave master Nathan MacKay in the Southern \"Slavesploitation\" drama ''[[Slaves (film)|Slaves]]'', also starring [[Ossie Davis]] and songstress [[Dionne Warwick]]. The film was loosely based on the famous [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]] novel ''[[Uncle Tom's Cabin]]''. It was filmed during the summer of 1968 at the supposedly haunted Buena Vista plantation near [[Shreveport]], [[Louisiana]] .<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19680905&id=6qUtAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5J8FAAAAIBAJ&pg=2688,534779&hl=en |title=Film being made about slavery |work=[[Montreal Gazette]] |page=8 |date=5 September 1968 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hauntla.com/buenavista.html|title=The Buena Vista Plantation|website=www.hauntla.com}}</ref> The film was released during the volatile civil rights era and in May 1969 Boyd attended the premiere alongside Dionne Warwick in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2205&dat=19690510&id=CO9fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HwMGAAAAIBAJ&pg=1448,3593309&hl=en |title=Opening Night |newspaper=[[Baltimore Afro-American]] |page=17 |date=10 May 1969 |accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> Closely following ''[[Slaves (film)|Slaves]]'', Boyd starred in another story about racial tension, this time a World War II made-for-television drama called ''Carter's Army'' (or ''Black Brigade'') which aired in August 1970, featuring a young [[Richard Pryor]].\n\nIt was around this time that Boyd began his interest in [[L. Ron Hubbard]]'s Church of [[Scientology]], which would make him one of the first Hollywood stars to be involved in it.<ref>''Scientology Auditor Magazine'', 1968 article, https://mikemcclaughry.wordpress.com/2016/03/19/blast-from-the-past-ben-hur-actor-stephen-boyd-featured-in-scientology-auditor-mag-1968/</ref>  Boyd had always expressed an interest in esoteric religions.<ref name=Loner>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1356&dat=19660906&id=tMwwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-QUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3955,901669&hl=en \"Stephen Boyd; Loner Who Is Never Alone\"] ''Ocala Star Banner'', 6 September 1966</ref> In an interview in August 1969 with the Detroit Free Press, Boyd explained that Scientology had helped him through the filming of ''Slaves'', and that to him Scientology was \"a process used to make you capable of learning. Scientology is nothing. It means only what you want it to. It is not a church you go to pray, but a church that you go to learn. It is no good unless you apply it. It is the application.\"<ref>''Detroit Free Press'', 1 August 1969, \"Screen Star Stephen Boyd, Since that Chariot Race\"</ref>  Boyd apparently had been elevated to a Scientology Status of OC 6, a position beneath that of [[Clear (Scientology)|Clear]]. Boyd would actually go on to star and narrate a Scientology recruiting film called ''Freedom'' in 1970.<ref>\"Snapping America's Epidemic of Sudden Personality Change\" by Flo Conway, page 145 '...&nbsp;it turned out to be a Scientology meeting. We heard a lecture and saw the introductory film, which was narrated by Stephen Boyd, the film star. It started out in a planetarium and he was standing there as if Scientology had found the stars or something.</ref> A copy of this film can be found at the Library of Congress, but it is not available online via any Scientology resource,<ref>https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/search?searchArg=l+ron+hubbard+film+freedom&searchCode=GKEY^*&searchType=0&recCount=25&sk=en_US</ref> which may indicate a falling out Boyd had with Scientology using his name for recruiting purposes. There is no documentation of his later involvement with Scientology after the early 1970s.\n\n===1970s===\nDuring the 1970s the demand for Boyd in Hollywood diminished, so he focused his attention on European films and several television pilots and shows.<ref>\"Stephen Boyd Likes U.S. Best\" Associated Press, 1 March 1973 Bob Thomas interview with Stephen Boyd</ref> He made three films in Spain with director [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Nieves Conde]], including ''[[Marta (film)|Marta]]'' in 1970, ''[[The Great Swindle (1971 film)|The Great Swindle]]'' in 1971, and ''Casa Manchada'' in 1975. He worked with cult director [[Romain Gary]] in the drug thriller ''[[Kill!]]'' in 1971. He also made several Westerns, including ''[[Hannie Caulder]]'' with Raquel Welch in 1971, ''[[The Man Called Noon]]'' in 1973, ''[[Those Dirty Dogs]]'' in 1973, and ''Potato Fritz'' in 1976. Boyd continued to travel to a wide variety of locations to work, including [[Australia]] for ''[[The Hands of Cormac Joyce]]'' in 1972, [[South Africa]] for ''Control Factor'' and ''The Manipulator'' in 1972-1973, [[Jamaica]] for the scuba diving adventure ''[[The Treasure of Jamaica Reef]]'' in 1972, Florida for the television pilot ''[[Key West]]'' in 1973, and Hawaii in his last acting stint as a guest star on the popular television show ''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]'' in 1977. The episode ''Up the Rebels'' was the premiere episode of ''Hawaii Five-O''&apos;s tenth season, and it aired after Boyd's death on 15 September 1977. His most critically acclaimed role during the 1970s was as a colourful Irish gangster in the UK crime thriller ''[[The Squeeze (1977 film)|The Squeeze]]'' in 1977.\n\nA letter from film producer [[Euan Lloyd]] (who produced such films as ''Shalako'', ''The Man Called Noon'' and ''The Wild Geese''), states that \"Stephen Boyd was one of the nicest, kindest people I have met in my lifetime, rare in this profession.\"<ref>Cushnan, Joe [https://archive.is/20140629144624/http://www.feedaread.com/books/Stephen-Boyd-From-Belfast-To-Hollywood-9781782990864.aspx ''Stephen Boyd: From Belfast To Hollywood''] {{ISBN|9781782990864}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Boyd spent most of his adult life traveling abroad for film work, he made his permanent home in southern [[California]]. At one point in the 1960s, he had three homes there \u2014 one above the Sunset Strip, one in [[Tarzana, Los Angeles|Tarzana]] and another in [[Palm Springs]], where he enjoyed his favorite pastime, golf.<ref name=Loner/> He would make frequent trips back to his hometown of [[Belfast]] in [[Northern Ireland]].<ref>''The Daily Reporter'', Dover, OH, 23 March 1968</ref> to visit his family. On one particular visit to [[Belfast]] in 1971, Boyd exclaimed his dismay about the situation in [[Northern Ireland]] at that time: \"Because of the divisiveness, the potential for displaying to the world all that is good in that lovely land is lost, perhaps even destroyed.\" Boyd was valued so highly by his native city of [[Belfast]] that during his visits he was always given a military escort from the airport to his home for security reasons during [[The Troubles]].<ref name=\"Tower Ticker\">Wiedrich, Bob. ''Chicago Tribune'' \"Tower Ticker\", 5 November 1971</ref>\n\n==Death and commemoration==\nBoyd died unexpectedly of a massive [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] on 2 June 1977 at the age of 45 while playing golf with his wife Elizabeth Mills at the Porter Valley Country Club in [[Northridge, Los Angeles|Northridge, California]]. \"Stephen and Elizabeth were in a golf cart between the fifth and sixth tees when suddenly he said. 'I don't feel well. I don't think we should go on' and slumped over. Elizabeth dragged him out of the cart and gave him artificial respiration, but it was too late.\" <ref>''Detroit Free Press June 9, 1977''.</ref> He was in talks to play the role of the [[Regimental sergeant major|Regimental Sergeant Major]] in [[Euan Lloyd]]'s ''[[The Wild Geese]]'' before his death.<ref name=\"euanlloyd\">Euan Lloyd interview, ''Cinema Retro'' #1</ref>\n\nBoyd was cremated and his ashes were interred in [[Oakwood Memorial Park Cemetery]] in [[Chatsworth, Los Angeles|Chatsworth, California]]. His wife Elizabeth Mills Boyd was interred with him at the time of her death in 2007. Boyd is also remembered on his parents' grave in the Clandeboye Cemetery, Bangor, U.K.<ref name=\"newsletter.co.uk\"/>\n\nOn 4 July 2018, the Ulster History Circle, a voluntary organisation  which erects plaques across the province of Ulster to celebrate people of achievement, commemorated Stephen Boyd with a [[Blue plaque#Northern Ireland|blue plaque]] close to his birthplace <ref>https://goo.gl/maps/6YmUuLxVGwZSBQqq5</ref> at 'Moygara', Shore Road, Whitehouse ([[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]]).<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-44701189\n</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n''Silver Screen'' Magazine in 1960 wrote this about Boyd:\n\n{{quote|A supreme individualist, like most Irishman, he has a wonderful actor's face that easily switches from an engaging smile to sinister menace. Far handsomer in person than on the screen&nbsp;... Stephen Boyd is a lean (180 pounds), well built (six-foot-one) charmer of 31, with a dazzling dimple, light brown curly hair, fair skin and the kind of grey eyes which take on color from what he is wearing. A man of tremendous vitality, a typical Celt, in many roles he veers from humor to anger in the wink of an eye. He dresses conservatively; speaks wittily, and extremely well, though he confesses that he's had almost no formal schooling; is genial and friendly ('I have my brooding hours which wipe that grin off my face').<ref>''Silver Screen'' Magazine, June 1960; \"Stephen Boyd - Sex Appeal + Blarney\" by Maxine Block</ref>}}\n\nJournalist [[Florabel Muir]] described Boyd's appeal in a feature from 1966. \"I would think it has to be his ruggedly masculine good looks. Strong, even craggy features, a wide sympathetic mouth, firm chin, athletic build, wavy dark brown hair, roving 185-lb. frame \u2013 all that plus a musical voice and the savoir faire of a much-traveled fellow \u2013 his films have taken him to many places in the world, and a rolling stone acquires a high polish.\" <ref>Florabel Muir, Valley Morning Star, 18 September 1966</ref>\n\nPersonally, Boyd was popular with Hollywood columnists, including his friend [[Hedda Hopper]], as well as fellow actors and other members of the entertainment industry because of his charm and sense of humor. \"Boyd is the kind of a man who was born to make friends and he has been doing it most of his life...Boyd is a blue-eyed, curly-haired chunk of masculinity, who makes no attempt to hide the fact that he just plain likes people. On the set of ''Ben-Hur'' he rarely occupied the fancy portable dressing room set aside for his use. Instead, he spent his time between scenes sitting around and chatting with electricians, carpenters and his fellow actors. He will discuss any subject and enjoys a good argument. He can, like most Irishmen, sprinkle his talk with wit as well as sagacity.\" <ref>\"The Evening Standard\", Stephen Boyd Prefers Villain Role in ''Ben-Hur'', Pennsylvania, 14 October 1960</ref>\n\nBoyd was first married in 1958 to Italian-born MCA executive Mariella Di Sarzana during the filming of ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]''. They separated after just three weeks. Concerning his short-lived marriage to Sarzana, Boyd would explain, \"It was my fault. I'm an Irish so-and-so when I'm working. I hadn't been married a week when we both knew we had made a mistake. She is a nice girl but we were just not meant for each other. I suppose I wasn't ready for marriage. Maybe I was still too much of an adolescent.\" <ref>''Screen Album'', August\u2013October 1960, page 46.</ref> They officially divorced in early 1959.<ref>''The Free Lance-Star'' 20 December 1958, \"The Divorce Set\"</ref> After his divorce Boyd lived as a bachelor for most of his life, dating several prominent Hollywood starlets throughout the 1960s.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19600428&id=hQswAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_QAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5317,6024126&hl=en \"Stephen Boyd Serious In Romantic Ventures\"] ''Toledo Blade'', 28 April 1960</ref> His secretary Elizabeth Mills was a permanent resident at his Tarzana home during these years, though the two did not marry until 1974.<ref>''Movie Life Jan 1963'', article, \"Let me tell you about Steve Boyd (his very best friend reveals all\" and  The Courier Journal (Louisville Kentucky), 30 December 1962, \"Stephen Boyd is Glad he Escaped Cleopatra with Liz Taylor\" : Excerpt, \"There's an English girl who looks after his house in the Valley here, but marriage does not seem to be on their agenda.\"</ref>\n\nBoyd had a deep and lasting friendship with actress and French icon [[Brigitte Bardot]]. Boyd starred in two movies with Bardot&nbsp;\u2014 ''[[The Night Heaven Fell]]'' in 1958 and ''[[Shalako (film)|Shalako]]'' in 1968. During the filming of ''[[Shalako]]'' in Almeria, Spain, Bardot and Boyd's close relationship and open affection for each other sparked numerous rumors of a possible affair.<ref name=\"Photoplay Film 1968\">''Photoplay Film'', September 1968, \"Boyd and Bardot- the Truth Behind Those Rumors\"</ref> It even caused Brigitte's husband at the time, [[Gunter Sachs]], to ask for a divorce.<ref>''The Milwaukee Journal'', 8 March 1968</ref> In Bardot's autobiography, she described the events and states that Boyd \"was never her lover, but a tender and attentive friend.\"<ref>\"Stephen n'ayant jamais \u00e9t\u00e9 mon amant, mais uniquement un ami tendre et attentionn\u00e9!\" Bardot, Brigitte. ''Initials B.B.'', 1995</ref> In an interview with ''Photoplay Film'' in 1968, Boyd said, \"Bardot is always Bardot. She's marvelous. She's an enormous star and she's a unique, marvelous woman. I adore her.\" <ref name=\"Photoplay Film 1968\"/> Even though both actors denied the affair, the press was \"convinced there was a romance afoot, that Brigitte and Boyd openly displayed their affection for each other, but that publication of the report on their romance cooled it.\" <ref>\"Boyd on Bardot\", Photolay Film Monthly, September 1968, Raymond Palmer Interviews Stephen Boyd</ref>\n\n[[File:Dolores Hart en Stephen Boyd (1961).jpg|thumb|Hart and Boyd in 1961]]\nBoyd also had a close relationship with actress [[Dolores Hart]]. Hart describes what was her only romance with a co-star in her autobiography ''The Ear of the Heart''.<ref>Hart, Dolores. ''The Ear of the Heart'', 2013</ref> Boyd eventually rejected her advances, but they remained close friends even after she turned to the cloistered life of a nun in 1963. He visited her in 1966 at the Abbey of Regina Laudis in Connecticut and remained in communication with her until the early 1970s.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1368&dat=19660207&id=N3ZQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rRAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4614,1215354&hl=en \"Stephen Boyd to Visit Dolores Hart, now Nun\"] ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', 7 February 1966</ref>\n\nStephen Boyd's most passionate affair seems to have been with beautiful Austrian actress [[Marisa Mell]].<ref>http://marisa-mell.blogspot.com/2008/09/marta-or-dopo-di-che-uccide-il-maschio.htm</ref> They met while filming the movie ''[[Marta (film)|Marta]]'' in 1970. Boyd initially dodged Marisa Mell's amorous advances, but during the second film they made together, ''[[The Great Swindle (1971 film)|The Great Swindle]]'', the two became inseparable lovers.<ref name=\"Mell, Marisa. Coverlove, 1990\">Mell, Marisa. ''Coverlove'', 1990</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceC\">Schneider, Andre. ''Die Feuerblume: \u00dcber Marisa Mell und ihre Filme'', 2013</ref> They married in a gypsy camp on the outskirts of  [[Madrid]] in late 1971. The ceremony included a wrist cutting exchange of blood to seal their bond.<ref>''The Record Argus'', 26 October 1971, \"Boyd's Bride will be Blood Brother\"</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> The marriage was not considered legal, but Marisa Mell said, \"Who cares? In our minds it will be real.\"<ref>''The San Bernardino County Sun'', 10 November 1971</ref> According to Marisa Mell, their affair was so intense that while living in Rome they made a trip to the Italian town of Sarsina for a ritual exorcism at the Cathedral of St. Vicinius.<ref name=\"Mell, Marisa. Coverlove, 1990\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> Boyd abruptly broke off the affair after the intensity apparently became too much to bear.<ref name=\"Mell, Marisa. Coverlove, 1990\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> In early 1972, after Boyd's departure, Mell had this to say about the break-up of their relationship: \"We both believe in reincarnation, and we realized we've already been lovers in three different lifetimes, and in each one I made him suffer terribly.\"<ref>''The Akron Beacon Journal, June 16, 1972''</ref> For her part, Mell would fondly remember Boyd many years later in her autobiography 'Cover Love' from 1990, dedicating a whole chapter to their affair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marisa-mell.blogspot.com/search/label/Stephen%2BBoyd.|title=MARISA MELL|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nBoyd's last marriage took place in 1974 to Elizabeth Mills,<ref>''Detroit Free Press June 9, 1977 'Just a few of the late Stephen Boyd's closest friends knew that three years ago in London he married Elizabeth Mills, whom he had been going with for many years''</ref> a secretary at the British Arts Council, whom he had known since 1953. Elizabeth Mills followed Boyd to the United States in the late 1950s and was his personal assistant, friend and confidante for many years before marrying him in the mid-1970s.<ref>[http://www.allaboutstephenboyd.com/biography.htm Stephen Boyd infosite]; accessed 28 June 2014.</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Black 13]]'' (1953) as Policeman (uncredited)\n* ''[[Lilacs in the Spring]]'' (1954) as Beaumont's Poolside Companion (uncredited)\n* ''[[An Alligator Named Daisy]]'' (1955) as Albert O'Shannon\n* ''Born for Trouble'' (1955)\n* ''[[The Man Who Never Was]]'' (1956) as Patrick O'Reilly\n* ''[[A Hill in Korea]]'' (1956) as Pvt. Sims\n* ''[[Seven Waves Away]]'' (1957) as Will McKinley\n* ''[[Island in the Sun (film)|Island in the Sun]]'' (1957) as Euan Templeton\n* ''[[Seven Thunders (film)|Seven Thunders]]'' (1957) as Dave\n* ''[[The Night Heaven Fell|Les bijoutiers du clair de lune]]'' (1958) as Lambert\n* ''[[The Bravados]]'' (1958) as Bill Zachary\n* ''[[Woman Obsessed]]'' (1959) as Fred Carter\n* ''[[The Best of Everything (film)|The Best of Everything]]'' (1959) as Mike Rice\n* ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]'' (1959) as [[Messala (Ben-Hur)|Messala]]\n* ''[[The Big Gamble (1961 film)|The Big Gamble]]'' (1961) as Vic Brennan\n* ''[[Lisa (1962 film)|Lisa]]'' (1962) as Peter Jongman\n* ''[[Billy Rose's Jumbo|Jumbo]]'' (1962) as Sam Rawlins\n* ''[[Imperial Venus (film)|Imperial Venus]]'' (1962) as Jules de Canouville\n* ''[[The Third Secret (film)|The Third Secret]]'' (1964) as Alex Stedman\n* ''[[The Fall of the Roman Empire (film)|The Fall of the Roman Empire]]'' (1964) as Livius\n* ''[[Genghis Khan (1965 film)|Genghis Khan]]'' (1965) as Jamuga\n* ''[[The Oscar (film)|The Oscar]]'' (1966) as Frank Fane\n* ''[[The Poppy Is Also a Flower]]'' (1966) as Benson\n* ''[[Fantastic Voyage]]'' (1966) as Grant\n* ''[[The Bible: In the Beginning...]]'' (1966) as [[Nimrod]]\n* ''[[The Caper of the Golden Bulls]]'' (1967) as Peter Churchman\n* ''[[Assignment K]]'' (1968) as Philip Scott\n* ''[[Shalako (film)|Shalako]]'' (1968) as Bosky Fulton\n* ''[[Slaves (film)|Slaves]]'' (1969) as MacKay\n* ''[[Carter's Army]]'' (1970, TV Movie) as Capt. Beau Carter\n* ''Historia de una traici\u00f3n'' (1971) as Arturo\n* ''[[Marta (film)|Marta]]'' (1971) as Don Miguel\n* ''African Story'' (1971) as Arnold Tiller\n* ''[[Hannie Caulder]]'' (1971) as The Preacher (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Great Swindle (1971 film)|The Great Swindle]]'' (1971) as Dave Barton\n* ''[[Kill! Kill! Kill! Kill!]]'' (1971) as Brad Killian\n* ''[[The Devil Has Seven Faces]]'' (1972) as Le\u00f3n Urrut\u00eda, joyero\n* ''[[The Hands of Cormac Joyce]]'' (1972, TV Movie) as Cormac Joyce\n* ''[[Those Dirty Dogs]]'' (1973) as Cpt. Chadwood Willer\n* ''[[The Big Game (1972 film)|The Big Game]]'' (1973) as Leyton van Dyk\n* ''[[The Man Called Noon]]'' (1973) as Rimes\n* ''[[The Treasure of Jamaica Reef]]'' (1974) as Hugo Graham\n* ''[[The Left Hand of the Law]]'' (1975) as Lanza\n* ''L'uomo che sfid\u00f2 l'organizzazione'' (1975) as Inspector Stephen McCormick\n* ''Potato Fritz'' (1976) as Bill Ardisson\n* ''[[Lady Dracula]]'' (1977) as [[Count Dracula]]\n* ''[[The Squeeze (1977 film)|The Squeeze]]'' (1977) as Vic\n* ''[[Women in Hospital]]'' (1977) as Dr. Oberhoff\n* ''Impossible Love'' (1977) as Alvaro\n* ''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]'' (1977, TV Series) as Daniel Costigan (final appearance)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{IMDb name|0000963}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=20469|name=Stephen Boyd}}\n* {{findagrave|1629}}\n* http://leglatin.pagesperso-orange.fr/boyd/\n* https://stephenboydblog.wordpress.com\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-12135044 \"Stephen Boyd: The Busker Who Became a Screen Idol\"] BBC News; retrieved 23 July 2011\n* [http://www.literarybelfast.org/article/3794/the-man-who-never-was- \"The Man Who Never Was?\"] Literary Belfast; retrieved 23 July 2011\n{{Golden Globe Award Best Supporting Actor Motion Picture}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boyd, Stephen}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actor Golden Globe (film) winners]]\n[[Category:Male film actors from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Burials at Oakwood Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n[[Category:People from Ballyclare]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ballyclare High School]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox contract players]]\n[[Category:20th-century male actors from Northern Ireland]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: though\u2192through", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephen_Boyd"}
{"title_page": "Christopher Atkins", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{other people|Chris Atkins}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Christopher Atkins\n| image       = Christopher_Atkins_2009.jpg\n| caption     = Atkins attending the [[Bench Warmer International|Bench Warmer]] Holiday Party at Empire, Hollywood, California on December 5, 2009\n| birth_name  = Christopher Atkins Bomann\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1961|2|21|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Rye, New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| occupation  = Actor\n| years_active = 1977&ndash;present\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Lyn Barron|1985|2007|end=div.}}\n| children    = Grant Bomann<br />Brittney Bomann\n}}\n\n'''Christopher Atkins''' (born '''Christopher Atkins Bomann''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/education/news-wires-white-papers-and-books/atkins-christopher-1961|title=Atkins, Christopher 1961\u2013 &#124; Encyclopedia.com|website=www.encyclopedia.com}}</ref> February 21, 1961)<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\">{{cite web|url=https://dailyvoice.com/new-york/rye/neighbors/happy-birthday-to-ryes-christopher-atkins/434296/|title=Happy Birthday To Rye's Christopher Atkins|date=February 21, 2014|website=Rye Daily Voice}}</ref> is an American actor who became famous following his debut film role in the 1980 film ''[[The Blue Lagoon (1980 film)|The Blue Lagoon]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nChristopher Atkins Bomann was born<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> and raised<ref name=\"people.com\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/from-the-depths-vol-54-no-15/|title=From the Depths|website=People.com|last=Tauber|first=Michelle|date=October 9, 2000}}</ref> in [[Rye, New York]]. He is the son of Donald Bomann and Bitsy Nebauer, who divorced during his childhood.<ref name=\"people.com1\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/look-out-j-r-chris-atkins-is-muscling-in-on-the-action-as-dallas-beefs-up-its-cast-vol-20-no-2/|title=Look Out, J.R.\u2014Chris Atkins Is Muscling in on the Action as Dallas Beefs Up Its Cast|last=Wallace|first=\nDavid|website=People.com|date=July 11, 1983}}</ref> Atkins was an aspiring baseball player; when his baseball aspirations were derailed by knee problems, he started a modeling career. When he began acting, Atkins dropped the last name Bomann and used his middle name, Atkins, as his last name.<ref name=\"people.com\"/>\n\n==Career==\nA friend suggested that Atkins audition for ''The Blue Lagoon''.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> Atkins won the role over thousands of other actors; the film's director, Randal Kleiser, has said that Atkins was a sailing instructor with no acting experience when he was cast in the film.<ref name=\"people.com\"/> In the film, he and co-star [[Brooke Shields]] played two teenaged cousins who find love while living in an isolated tropical paradise after being marooned as children.<ref name=\"Much\"/> Released in 1980, the film grossed over $58 million with a production cost of $4.5 million<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Blue-Lagoon-The#tab=summary | title=The Blue Lagoon (1980) - Financial Information |work=The-Numbers.com|access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/56372|website=AFI.com|title=AFI Catalog of Feature Films: The First 100 Years 1893\u20131993|access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/21857%7C0/The-Blue-Lagoon.html|title=The Blue Lagoon|website=Turner Classic Movies|access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref> but received a negative critical response.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/blue_lagoon/|title=The Blue Lagoon|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref> Atkins appeared nude<ref name=\"Much\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/cover-story-too-much-too-young-vol-14-no-6/|title=Too Much, Too Young?|work=People|last=McMurrin|first=Kristin|date=August 11, 1980|access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/entertainment-news/2009/01/29/christopher-atkins-poster-child-gay-rights-movement|title=Christopher Atkins: Poster Child for Gay Rights Movement?|work=Advocate.com|date=January 9, 2009|access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref> (including frontal nudity<ref name=\"Chris Atkins\">{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodshow.com/starDetail.php?id=3|title=Chris Atkins|work=HollywoodShow.com|access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref>) in the film, and spent much of the film wearing a loincloth.<ref name=\"people.com1\"/> While ''Blue Lagoon'' was controversial due to its nude scenes and sexual content,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/chazs-blog/sexualized-innocence-revisiting-the-blue-lagoon|title=Sexualized Innocence: Revisiting The Blue Lagoon| first=Abbey|last=Bender|website=www.RogerEbert.com|date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> it nevertheless became a \"pop culture phenomenon\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/the-blue-lagoon-turns-35-trivia-for-brooke-shields-and-christopher-atkins-film/|title=Celebrate The Blue Lagoon's 35th Anniversary with 10 Movie Facts You Should Know|website=People.com|last=Mackie |first=Drew |date=July 1, 2015}}</ref> Atkins was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Award]] for New Star of the Year in a Motion Picture \u2013 Male for ''The Blue Lagoon''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2012/03/denise-richards-blue-lagoon-remake-christopher-atkins-cameo-241315/|title=Denise Richards To Co-Star In 'Blue Lagoon' Reboot, Christopher Atkins To Make Cameo|first1=Nellie|last1=Andreeva|work=Deadline.com|date=March 8, 2012}}</ref> \n[[File:Chris Atkins 1981.jpg|thumb|left|Atkins in 1981]] \nAtkins posed nude for ''[[Playgirl]]''<ref name=\"people.com1\"/> in 1982.<ref name=\"Chris Atkins\"/> He went on to star with [[Kristy McNichol]] in ''[[The Pirate Movie]]'' (1982), an update of [[Gilbert and Sullivan]]'s operetta ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]''.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> His song \"How Can I Live Without Her\", which peaked at #71 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], was played in the film.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> Atkins portrayed Rick Monroe, a college student working as an exotic dancer, in ''[[A Night in Heaven]]'' (1983);<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> he won the 1983 Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actor for his performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vancourier.com/opinion/reliving-reckless-by-bryan-adams-1.2179670|title=Reliving Reckless by Bryan Adams|last=Fleming|first=Andrew|website=Vancouver Courier|date=November 27, 2014}}</ref> For one season (1983\u20131984), Atkins had a recurring role as camp counselor Peter Richards on ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]''.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/>\n\nAtkins appeared in the television situation comedy ''Suddenly Susan'', which starred Shields, in 1999.<ref name=\"people.com\"/> In 2009, Atkins appeared on [[VH1]]'s ''[[Confessions of a Teen Idol]]'', a reality show featuring former teen idols.<ref name=\"ew.com\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2009/01/02/christopher-atk/|title=Christopher Atkins: PopWatch 'Teen Idol' Q&A (Part 4 of 4)|website=EW.com|last=Bierly |first=Mandy| date=January 2, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.boston.com/ae/tv/articles/2009/01/06/idol_hopes_underlie_these_confessions/|title=Idol hopes underlie these 'Confessions'|first=Mary|last=McNamara|date=January 6, 2009|via=The Boston Globe}}</ref> He has been ranked no. 76 on VH1's list of 100 Greatest Teen Stars.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/>\n\nAtkins became a luxury pool builder.<ref name=\"ew.com\"/> He also developed the Christopher Atkins Strike Jacket E.F.L. (Extreme Fishing Lure)--\"a rubbery slipcovering for traditional baits\"--with the assistance of special-effects expert Mark Viniello.<ref name=\"people.com\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Brittney Bomann and Christopher Atkins.JPG|right|thumb|Atkins and his daughter on the red carpet at the 62nd&nbsp;Annual Mother Goose Parade in San Diego County, 2008]]\nAtkins married Lynne Barron Weber of [[Sydney, Australia]], on 25&nbsp;May 1985. The couple have two children: Son Grant Bomann and daughter Brittney Bomann.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/actor-christopher-atkins-wife-lyn-barron-daughter-brittney-news-photo/142000266 |series=Ron Galella archive |year=2012 |title=Actor Christopher Atkins, wife Lyn Barron, daughter Brittney Bomann and son Grant Bomann |access-date=31 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nndb.com/people/819/000025744/ |title=Christopher Atkins |website=nndb.com |access-date=31 July 2015}}</ref> The couple divorced in 2007.<ref name=People200902>{{cite web |url=https://people.com/archive/christopher-atkins-second-act-vol-71-no-6/ |title=Christopher Atkins second act |magazine=People |volume=71 |issue=6 |last=Rizzo |first=Monica |date=16 February 2009 |access-date=23 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2009 interview, Atkins acknowledged his past struggle with alcoholism and stated that he had been sober for 22&nbsp;years.<ref name=People200902/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Div col}}\n* ''[[The Blue Lagoon (1980 film)|The Blue Lagoon]]'' (1980) as Richard Lestrange\n* ''[[Swan Lake (1981 film)|Swan Lake]]'' (1981) (voice) as Prince Siegfried\n* ''[[Child Bride of Short Creek]]'' (1981) ([[television film|TV]]) as Isaac King\n* ''[[Aladdin and the Wonderful Lamp (1982 film)|Aladdin and the Magic Lamp]]'' (1982) (voice) as Aladdin\n* ''[[The Pirate Movie]]'' (1982) as Frederic\n* ''[[A Night in Heaven]]'' (1983) as Rick Monroe\n* ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]'' (1983\u201384) as Peter Richards\n* ''Secret Weapons'' (1985) as Allan Collier\n* ''Beaks: The Movie'' (1987) as Peter\n* ''[[Mortuary Academy]]'' (1988) as Max Grimm\n* ''[[Listen to Me (film)|Listen to Me]]'' (1989) as Bruce Arlington\n* ''[[Shakma]]'' (1990) as Sam\n* ''[[Fatal Charm (1990 film)|Fatal Charm]]'' (1990) as Adam\n* ''King's Ransom'' (1991) as Spence\n* ''Extralarge: Miami Killer'' (1991) as Blake\n* ''[[Exchange Lifeguards|Wet and Wild Summer!]]'' (1992) as Bobby McCain\n* ''Dracula Rising'' (1993) as Vlad\n* ''[[Die Watching]]'' (1993) as Michael Terrence\n* ''[[\u00a1Dispara!]]'' (1993) as Spence\n* ''Trigger Fast'' (1994) as Dusty Fog\n* ''[[Signal One]]'' (1994) as Martin Bullet\n* ''Guns of Honor'' (1994) as Dusty Fog\n* ''[[Bandit (film series)|Bandit Goes Country]]'' (1994) as Johnny Bruce\n* ''Smoke n Lightnin'' (1995) as Lightnin'\n* ''[[Project Shadowchaser III]]'' (1995) as Snake\n* ''[[Red Shoe Diaries]]'' (1996) (segment \"Four on the Floor\")\n* ''[[It's My Party (film)|It's My Party]]'' (1996) as Jack Allen\n* ''[[Dead Man's Island]]'' (1996) (TV) as Roger Prescott\n* ''Angel Flight Down'' (1996) as Jack Bahr\n* ''[[Mutual Needs]]'' (1997) as Andrew\n* ''Shoot'' (1998) as Spence\n* ''[[Lima: Breaking the Silence]]'' (1998) as Jeff\n* ''Deadly Delusions'' (1999) as Sam Gitlin\n* ''Stageghost'' (2000) as Matthew Bronson\n* ''[[Dark Realm]]'' (2000) ([[TV Series]])\n* ''Civility'' (2000) as John Cade\n* ''[[Title to Murder]]'' (2001) as Paul Shaughnessy\n* ''[[The Little Unicorn]]'' (2001) as PC Sid Edwards\n* ''Tequila Express'' (2002) as David Manning\n* ''The Stoneman'' (2002) as Kip Hollings\n* ''[[Mending Fences]]'' (2002) as Tom\n* ''The Employee of the Month'' (2002) as Bill\n* ''The Color of Water'' (2002) as Clay\n* ''[[13th Child]]'' (2002) as Ron\n* ''[[Quigley (film)|Quigley]]'' (2003) as Woodward Channing\n* ''True Legends of the West'' (2003) as Theodore Sutherland\n* ''[[The Librarians (film)|The Librarians]]'', a.k.a. ''Strike Force'', (2004) as Ringo\n* ''[[Caved In: Prehistoric Terror]]'' (2005) as John Palmer\n* ''Spiritual Warriors'' (2005) as King of Sparta\n* ''[[100 Million BC]]'' (2007) as Erik Reno\n* ''[[Cach\u00e9 (film)|Hidden]]'' (2008) as Walter\n* ''Chinaman's Chance: America's Yellow Slaves'' (2008) as Jacob\n* ''[[Forget Me Not (2009 film)|Forget Me Not]]'' (2008) as Mr. Channing \n* ''[[Confessions of a Teen Idol]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Exodus Fall]]'' (2009) as Wayne Minor\n* ''[[Gathering of Heroes: Legend of the Seven Swords]]'' (2009) as Garrik Grayraven\n* ''The Hard Ride'' (2009) as George Custer\n* ''Prism'' (2009) as Detective Shane Dover\n* ''The Earth Empires: Ottoman Invasion'' (2010) as jannisery Commander Murat of the Dark\n* ''Harley's Hill'' (2011) as Mr. Miller\n* ''[[Blue Lagoon: The Awakening]]'' (2012) as Mr. Christiansen\n* ''Waiting in the Wings: The Musical'' (2014) as Priest\n* ''A Horse for Summer'' (2015) as Pastor Bob\n* ''Kids vs. Monsters'' (2015) as Charles\n* ''The Sparrows'' (2015) as Mike Sparrow\n* ''One Remains'' (2019) as Samuel Mahoney\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Facebook|christopher.atkins.509}}\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|803}}\n* {{AllMovie name|2694}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atkins, Christopher}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:People from Rye, New York]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{other people|Chris Atkins}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Christopher Atkins\n| image       = Christopher_Atkins_2009.jpg\n| caption     = Atkins attending the [[Bench Warmer International|Bench Warmer]] Holiday Party at Empire, Hollywood, California on December 5, 2009\n| birth_name  = Christopher Atkins Bomann\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1961|2|21|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Rye, New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| occupation  = Actor\n| years_active = 1977&ndash;present\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Lyn Barron|1985|2007|end=div.}}\n| children    = Grant Bomann<br />Brittney Bomann\n}}\n\n'''Christopher Atkins''' (born '''Christopher Atkins Bomann''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/education/news-wires-white-papers-and-books/atkins-christopher-1961|title=Atkins, Christopher 1961\u2013 &#124; Encyclopedia.com|website=www.encyclopedia.com}}</ref> February 21, 1961)<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\">{{cite web|url=https://dailyvoice.com/new-york/rye/neighbors/happy-birthday-to-ryes-christopher-atkins/434296/|title=Happy Birthday To Rye's Christopher Atkins|date=February 21, 2014|website=Rye Daily Voice}}</ref> is an American actor who became famous following his debut film role in the 1980 film ''[[The Blue Lagoon (1980 film)|The Blue Lagoon]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nChristopher Atkins Bomann was born<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> and raised<ref name=\"people.com\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/from-the-depths-vol-54-no-15/|title=From the Depths|website=People.com|last=Tauber|first=Michelle|date=October 9, 2000}}</ref> in [[Rye, New York]]. He is the son of Donald Bomann and Bitsy Nebauer, who divorced during his childhood.<ref name=\"people.com1\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/look-out-j-r-chris-atkins-is-muscling-in-on-the-action-as-dallas-beefs-up-its-cast-vol-20-no-2/|title=Look Out, J.R.\u2014Chris Atkins Is Muscling in on the Action as Dallas Beefs Up Its Cast|last=Wallace|first=\nDavid|website=People.com|date=July 11, 1983}}</ref> Atkins was an aspiring baseball player; when his baseball aspirations were derailed by knee problems, he started a modeling career. When he began acting, Atkins dropped the last name Bomann and used his middle name, Atkins, as his last name.<ref name=\"people.com\"/>\n\n==Career==\nA friend suggested that Atkins audition for ''The Blue Lagoon''.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> Atkins won the role over thousands of other actors; the film's director, Randal Kleiser, has said that Atkins was a sailing instructor with no acting experience when he was cast in the film.<ref name=\"people.com\"/> In the film, he and co-star [[Brooke Shields]] played two teenaged cousins who find love while living in an isolated tropical paradise after being marooned as children.<ref name=\"Much\"/> Released in 1980, the film grossed over $58 million with a production cost of $4.5 million<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Blue-Lagoon-The#tab=summary | title=The Blue Lagoon (1980) - Financial Information |work=The-Numbers.com|access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/56372|website=AFI.com|title=AFI Catalog of Feature Films: The First 100 Years 1893\u20131993|access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/21857%7C0/The-Blue-Lagoon.html|title=The Blue Lagoon|website=Turner Classic Movies|access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref> but received a negative critical response.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/blue_lagoon/|title=The Blue Lagoon|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref> Atkins appeared nude<ref name=\"Much\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/cover-story-too-much-too-young-vol-14-no-6/|title=Too Much, Too Young?|work=People|last=McMurrin|first=Kristin|date=August 11, 1980|access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/entertainment-news/2009/01/29/christopher-atkins-poster-child-gay-rights-movement|title=Christopher Atkins: Poster Child for Gay Rights Movement?|work=Advocate.com|date=January 9, 2009|access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref> (including frontal nudity<ref name=\"Chris Atkins\">{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodshow.com/starDetail.php?id=3|title=Chris Atkins|work=HollywoodShow.com|access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref>) in the film, and spent much of the film wearing a loincloth.<ref name=\"people.com1\"/> While ''Blue Lagoon'' was controversial due to its nude scenes and sexual content,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/chazs-blog/sexualized-innocence-revisiting-the-blue-lagoon|title=Sexualized Innocence: Revisiting The Blue Lagoon| first=Abbey|last=Bender|website=www.RogerEbert.com|date=March 4, 2019}}</ref> it nevertheless became a \"pop culture phenomenon\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/the-blue-lagoon-turns-35-trivia-for-brooke-shields-and-christopher-atkins-film/|title=Celebrate The Blue Lagoon's 35th Anniversary with 10 Movie Facts You Should Know|website=People.com|last=Mackie |first=Drew |date=July 1, 2015}}</ref> Atkins was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Award]] for New Star of the Year in a Motion Picture \u2013 Male for ''The Blue Lagoon''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2012/03/denise-richards-blue-lagoon-remake-christopher-atkins-cameo-241315/|title=Denise Richards To Co-Star In 'Blue Lagoon' Reboot, Christopher Atkins To Make Cameo|first1=Nellie|last1=Andreeva|work=Deadline.com|date=March 8, 2012}}</ref> \n[[File:Chris Atkins 1981.jpg|thumb|left|Atkins in 1981]] \nAtkins posed nude for ''[[Playgirl]]''<ref name=\"people.com1\"/> in 1982.<ref name=\"Chris Atkins\"/> He went on to star with [[Kristy McNichol]] in ''[[The Pirate Movie]]'' (1982), an update of [[Gilbert and Sullivan]]'s operetta ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]''.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> His song \"How Can I Live Without Her\", which peaked at #71 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], was played in the film.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> Atkins portrayed Rick Monroe, a college student working as an exotic dancer, in ''[[A Night in Heaven]]'' (1983);<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/> he won the 1983 Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actor for his performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vancourier.com/opinion/reliving-reckless-by-bryan-adams-1.2179670|title=Reliving Reckless by Bryan Adams|last=Fleming|first=Andrew|website=Vancouver Courier|date=November 27, 2014}}</ref> For one season (1983\u20131984), Atkins had a recurring role as camp counselor Peter Richards on ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]''.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/>\n\nAtkins appeared in the television situation comedy ''Suddenly Susan'', which starred Shields, in 1999.<ref name=\"people.com\"/> In 2009, Atkins appeared on [[VH1]]'s ''[[Confessions of a Teen Idol]]'', a reality show featuring former teen idols.<ref name=\"ew.com\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2009/01/02/christopher-atk/|title=Christopher Atkins: PopWatch 'Teen Idol' Q&A (Part 4 of 4)|website=EW.com|last=Bierly |first=Mandy| date=January 2, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.boston.com/ae/tv/articles/2009/01/06/idol_hopes_underlie_these_confessions/|title=Idol hopes underlie these 'Confessions'|first=Mary|last=McNamara|date=January 6, 2009|via=The Boston Globe}}</ref> He has been ranked no. 76 on VH1's list of 100 Greatest Teen Stars.<ref name=\"dailyvoice.com\"/>\n\nAtkins became a luxury pool builder.<ref name=\"ew.com\"/> He also developed the Christopher Atkins Strike Jacket E.F.L. (Extreme Fishing Lure)--\"a rubbery slipcovering for traditional baits\"--with the assistance of special-effects expert Mark Viniello.<ref name=\"people.com\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Brittney Bomann and Christopher Atkins.JPG|right|thumb|Atkins and his daughter on the red carpet at the 62nd&nbsp;Annual Mother Goose Parade in San Diego County, 2008]]\nAtkins married Lynne Barron Weber of [[Sydney, Australia]], on 25&nbsp;May 1985. The couple have two children: Son Grant Bomann and daughter Brittney Bomann.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/actor-christopher-atkins-wife-lyn-barron-daughter-brittney-news-photo/142000266 |series=Ron Galella archive |year=2012 |title=Actor Christopher Atkins, wife Lyn Barron, daughter Brittney Bomann and son Grant Bomann |access-date=31 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nndb.com/people/819/000025744/ |title=Christopher Atkins |website=nndb.com |access-date=31 July 2015}}</ref> The couple divorced in 2007.<ref name=People200902>{{cite web |url=https://people.com/archive/christopher-atkins-second-act-vol-71-no-6/ |title=Christopher Atkins second act |magazine=People |volume=71 |issue=6 |last=Rizzo |first=Monica |date=16 February 2009 |access-date=23 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2009 interview, Atkins acknowledged his past struggle with alcoholism and stated that he had been sober for 22&nbsp;years.<ref name=People200902/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Div col}}\n* ''[[The Blue Lagoon (1980 film)|The Blue Lagoon]]'' (1980) as Richard Lestrange\n* ''[[Swan Lake (1981 film)|Swan Lake]]'' (1981) (voice) as Prince Siegfried\n* ''[[Child Bride of Short Creek]]'' (1981) ([[television film|TV]]) as Isaac King\n* ''[[Aladdin and the Wonderful Lamp (1982 film)|Aladdin and the Magic Lamp]]'' (1982) (voice) as Aladdin\n* ''[[The Pirate Movie]]'' (1982) as Frederic\n* ''[[A Night in Heaven]]'' (1983) as Rick Monroe\n* ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]'' (1983\u201384) as Peter Richards\n* ''Secret Weapons'' (1985) as Allan Collier\n* ''Beaks: The Movie'' (1987) as Peter\n* ''[[Mortuary Academy]]'' (1988) as Max Grimm\n* ''[[Listen to Me (film)|Listen to Me]]'' (1989) as Bruce Arlington\n* ''[[Shakma]]'' (1990) as Sam\n* ''[[Fatal Charm (1990 film)|Fatal Charm]]'' (1990) as Adam\n* ''King's Ransom'' (1991) as Spence\n* ''Extralarge: Miami Killer'' (1991) as Blake\n* ''[[Exchange Lifeguards|Wet and Wild Summer!]]'' (1992) as Bobby McCain\n* ''Dracula Rising'' (1993) as Vlad\n* ''[[Die Watching]]'' (1993) as Michael Terrence\n* ''[[\u00a1Dispara!]]'' (1993) as Spence\n* ''Trigger Fast'' (1994) as Dusty Fog\n* ''[[Signal One]]'' (1994) as Martin Bullet\n* ''Guns of Honor'' (1994) as Dusty Fog\n* ''[[Bandit (film series)|Bandit Goes Country]]'' (1994) as Johnny Bruce\n* ''Smoke n Lightnin'' (1995) as Lightnin'\n* ''[[Project Shadowchaser III]]'' (1995) as Snake\n* ''[[Red Shoe Diaries]]'' (1996) (segment \"Four on the Floor\")\n* ''[[It's My Party (film)|It's My Party]]'' (1996) as Jack Allen\n* ''[[Dead Man's Island]]'' (1996) (TV) as Roger Prescott\n* ''Angel Flight Down'' (1996) as Jack Bahr\n* ''[[Mutual Needs]]'' (1997) as Andrew\n* ''Shoot'' (1998) as Spence\n* ''[[Lima: Breaking the Silence]]'' (1998) as Jeff\n* ''Deadly Delusions'' (1999) as Sam Gitlin\n* ''Stageghost'' (2000) as Matthew Bronson\n* ''[[Dark Realm]]'' (2000) ([[TV Series]])\n* ''Civility'' (2000) as John Cade\n* ''[[Title to Murder]]'' (2001) as Paul Shaughnessy\n* ''[[The Little Unicorn]]'' (2001) as PC Sid Edwards\n* ''Tequila Express'' (2002) as David Manning\n* ''The Stoneman'' (2002) as Kip Hollings\n* ''[[Mending Fences]]'' (2002) as Tom\n* ''The Employee of the Month'' (2002) as Bill\n* ''The Color of Water'' (2002) as Clay\n* ''[[13th Child]]'' (2002) as Ron\n* ''[[Quigley (film)|Quigley]]'' (2003) as Woodward Channing\n* ''True Legends of the West'' (2003) as Theodore Sutherland\n* ''[[The Librarians (film)|The Librarians]]'', a.k.a. ''Strike Force'', (2004) as Ringo\n* ''[[Caved In: Prehistoric Terror]]'' (2005) as John Palmer\n* ''Spiritual Warriors'' (2005) as King of Sparta\n* ''[[100 Million BC]]'' (2007) as Erik Reno\n* ''[[Cach\u00e9 (film)|Hidden]]'' (2008) as Walter\n* ''Chinaman's Chance: America's Yellow Slaves'' (2008) as Jacob\n* ''[[Forget Me Not (2009 film)|Forget Me Not]]'' (2008) as Mr. Channing \n* ''[[Confessions of a Teen Idol]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Exodus Fall]]'' (2009) as Wayne Minor\n* ''[[Gathering of Heroes: Legend of the Seven Swords]]'' (2009) as Garrik Grayraven\n* ''The Hard Ride'' (2009) as George Custer\n* ''Prism'' (2009) as Detective Shane Dover\n* ''The Earth Empires: Ottoman Invasion'' (2010) as jannisery Commander Murat of the Dark\n* ''Harley's Hill'' (2011) as Mr. Miller\n* ''[[Blue Lagoon: The Awakening]]'' (2012) as Mr. Christiansen\n* ''Waiting in the Wings: The Musical'' (2014) as Priest\n* ''A Horse for Summer'' (2015) as Pastor Bob\n* ''Kids vs. Monsters'' (2015) as Charles\n* ''The Sparrows'' (2015) as Mike Sparrow\n* ''One Remains'' (film) (2019) as Samuel Mahoney\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Facebook|christopher.atkins.509}}\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|803}}\n* {{AllMovie name|2694}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atkins, Christopher}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:People from Rye, New York]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilmography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christopher_Atkins"}
